(1,1,'傳譯簡介	','','','','',0,'2021-02-24 18:48:44',NULL,NULL),
(2,2,'複述和撮述	','Ex 2.1  \r\nReference \r\nThe Transport Department has updated the Road Users’ Code in use since 2000. It includes  new requirements like wearing seat belts, switching off idling engines, as well as on cycling  and traffic signs etc. It will affect the driving test and taxi written test.  \r\nSource: \r\nHong Kong SAR Government. (2020). Road Users’ Code Updated.  \r\nhttps://www.news.gov.hk/eng/2020/06/20200619/20200619_164253_675.html\r\n','Ex 2.1  \r\nReference \r\nThe Transport Department has updated the Road Users’ Code in use since 2000. It includes  new requirements like wearing seat belts, switching off idling engines, as well as on cycling  and traffic signs etc. It will affect the driving test and taxi written test.  \r\nSource: \r\nHong Kong SAR Government. (2020). Road Users’ Code Updated.  \r\nhttps://www.news.gov.hk/eng/2020/06/20200619/20200619_164253_675.html\r\n','Ex 2.2\r\nReference\r\n情緒，經常被認為是不好的東西，由我這一代到新一代均如是。然而，情緒一直沒有\r\n被淘汰，原因是它能夠救命。\r\nSource:\r\n陳永儀。（2016）。沒有「負面能量」是好事嗎？需要重新認識的「情緒反應」。\r\nTEDxTalks。https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiJ4zibW8_M','Ex 2.2\r\nReference\r\n情緒，經常被認為是不好的東西，由我這一代到新一代均如是。然而，情緒一直沒有\r\n被淘汰，原因是它能夠救命。\r\nSource:\r\n陳永儀。（2016）。沒有「負面能量」是好事嗎？需要重新認識的「情緒反應」。\r\nTEDxTalks。https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uiJ4zibW8_M',0,'2021-02-24 18:50:13',NULL,NULL),
(3,3,'視譯(英譯中)	','By encouraging consumption and continually increasing production, the fashion industry has reached a new peak in its historical development. But this has given rise to a many environmental problems.\r\n\r\nAccording to Greenpeace, each year Taiwanese consumers aged 20-45 discard at least 5.2 million pieces of clothing, meaning that on average 9.9 garments are being thrown into trash cans or clothes recycling bins every minute.\r\n\r\nAnother problem is carbon emissions. Cheap manmade fiber is very useful, but three times as much carbon dioxide is released in its production as for raw cotton. At present more than 60% of textile fibers made are synthetic fibers produced from fossil ¬fuels, and clothing made from synthetic fibers doesn’t rot down when it reaches landfill. This prompted the New York Times to comment mockingly that future archeologists may study the fast fashion retailer ZARA in ancient landfills. Also, microfibers that come off clothing when it is washed are swept into streams and oceans, where they persist for thousands of years without decomposing.\r\n\r\nA number of dedicated people are taking action to reduce pollution from the fashion industry. Some famous designers have begun to incorporate sustainability into their catwalk designs, for example by using purely natural cotton or hemp materials for their attire and rejecting the use of manmade petro¬chemical fibers. Still others have altered production processes or extended the life expect¬ancy of products, or are using re¬cycling to give new value to products and turn waste into gold.\r\n','鼓勵消費，不斷生產，時尚產業來到史上發展的最巔峰，卻也衍生許多環境問題。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n根據綠色和平組織統計，台灣20-45歲的民眾，每年至少丟棄520萬件衣服，等於每分鐘有9.9件衣服被丟進垃圾桶或是舊衣回收箱。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n另一個問題是碳排放。廉價的人造纖維材質相當好用，但是製程中釋放出的二氧化碳，是棉花的三倍。現在有超過60％的織物纖維是石化燃料衍生的合成纖維，因此在衣服被丟棄而進入垃圾掩埋場後，並不會腐化，因此紐約時報以揶揄的口氣報導，未來的考古學家可能會在遠古垃圾掩埋場研究ZARA，而洗滌時從衣物掉落的超細纖維被沖入溪流、海洋，這些微塑膠也是千年不會腐化。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n要扭轉時尚產業污染，一些有志之士已經付諸行動。部分知名時裝設計師開始把永續議題帶上伸展台，例如用純天然的綿、麻材質設計服飾，拒絕使用石化人造纖維。還有一些人改變製程或延長產品終點，透過回收再造，賦予產品全新的價值，讓廢棄物點石成金。','The United Nations anticipates that by 2030 there will be 43 megacities worldwide with populations of more than 10 million people, and that by 2050 nearly 70% of the world’s population will live in cities.\r\n\r\nCity governments around the world have become focused on making their cities “smarter.” One aspect of this involves sustainably developed low-carbon smart cities, which the European Union began promoting in 2007. Amsterdam, which has been pursuing numerous projects to use energy-¬saving technologies to reduce CO2 emissions and energy consumption, provides one example of the EU’s efforts. In the United States, the city of Seattle has developed a “smart grid” that helps save energy. In Japan, the i-Japan program is promoting the development of ICT businesses as a stepping stone to a “smart society.” Smart city development strategies are advancing around the world.\r\n\r\nIn Europe the focus in the development of smart cities has gradually shifted from emerging technology applications and infrastructure construction to solving local problems. These new strategies are using civic participation and shared bottom-up platforms to gather public views and build “innovation economies.” For example, London has provided its citizens and businesses with an online platform called Talk London that elicits proposals to solve problems. Meanwhile, Finland organizes an annual technology and startup event called the Slush conference, and an urban hackathon that promotes startup opportunities and encourages innovative businesses to participate in city development.\r\n','根據聯合國預估，2030年將出現43個超過千萬人的巨型城市，到2050年全球將有70％人口居住在城市。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n打造智慧城市，成為全球各大城市重要的施政目標。歐盟從2007年開始推動永續發展的低碳智慧城市，例如荷蘭的阿姆斯特丹以多個專案計劃，通過節能技術，降低二氧化碳排放量和能量消耗。美國西雅圖發展「智慧電網計劃」以節約能源；日本的「i-Japan」計劃以促進ICT產業的發展，達到建立智慧型社會的目標，智慧城市儼然成為全球城市重要發展的策略與趨勢。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n然而全球智慧城市的發展策略也與時俱進。歐美智慧城市的發展，逐漸從注重新興科技應用或是推出基礎建設，轉向解決在地問題，透過建立公民參與、由下而上（Bottom up）的共享式平台，達到群眾集思與「創新經濟」的目的。例如倫敦針對市民、企業，提供網路平台「Talk London」，來共同激發出解決問題的提案；芬蘭創立科技創業週年聚會Slush，舉辦城市駭客松競賽（Hackathon），鼓勵創業機會，讓有創意的業者加入市政建設的行列。',0,'2021-02-24 18:52:13',NULL,NULL),
(4,4,'視譯(中譯英)	','2018年1月上線的「電電租」，是台灣第一個家電出租共享平台。民眾只要加入會員，將家電拍照上傳，填寫家電的品牌、型號、使用心得等資料，就能將家電上架，成為平台暱稱的「電租公」，將家電開放給網友搜尋。電電租透過幾個簡單的步驟就能將每個人的家電串聯，讓閒置家電發揮功用，還能為家電主人創造額外收入。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n電電租平台的創辦人表示，起初預設萬元的精品家電才有人租，所以訂定了兩種租金類型:周二租周五還租金500元，或是週六租週一還租金700元，不論品牌及種類，租金都只分成平日、假日兩種。實際運作後才發現家電租用的需求五花八門，就連幾千元的電鍋也有人願意以500元的價格租用。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n租借的族群大致可分為三種，一是有使用需求但不想買；另一種則是試用，確定符合需求再買。第三種族群是商用需求，例如有公司為了消除裝潢氣味，一口氣租了10台空氣清淨機；或是影視劇組租借精品家電，作為豪宅的場景布置等。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n電電租平台至今接過捕蚊燈、電磁爐、電鍋等各種需求，商務訂單常常一次就是10台以上的數量，平台的角色就是挖掘這些潛在資源。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n電電租跟大眾倡導物品的使用權，而不是擁有權。在循環經濟概念逐漸成熟的現在，產品服務化已是未來趨勢。\r\n','Homeapp123, which went online in January of 2018, is the first home appliance rental platform in Taiwan. After signing up as members, appliance owners can upload pictures of their appliances along with details including the brand, model, and any comments, to become “appliance renters” and make their appliances available to other Internet users. Through a few simple steps Homeapp123 can link together individuals so that idle appliances can be put to use and also earn some income on the side for their owners.\r\n\r\n\r\nFounders of the platform say that at first they expected that customers would only want to rent expensive high-end appliances, so they set up just two rental plans: Rent on Tuesday and return on Friday for $500, and rent on Saturday and return on Monday for $700. These were the same regardless of the type or brand of appliance. It was only after they began real operations that they discovered that demand for home appliance rentals was very diverse, and there were even people willing to pay $500 to rent an electric rice cooker that would cost only a few thousand dollars to buy new.\r\n\r\nRenters fall into three types: The first wishes to use an appliance with no intention of buying it, while the second plans to try it out, and to buy one for themselves if it fits their needs. The third type of renters are commercial users. For example, one company rented ten air purifiers through Homeapp123 to get rid of a lingering smell after redecorating, while a TV drama production company rented high-end appliances as props for a set depicting a luxury dwelling. \r\n\r\nThe Homeapp123 platform has accepted many commercial orders—often for ten or more appliances at a time—for items such as insect traps, induction cookers, and rice cookers. Its role is to help renters tap into the huge resource represented by the appliances kept in individual households.\r\n\r\nHomeapp123 urges people to think in terms of “right of use” rather than “ownership.” As the concept of the circular economy matures, turning products into services will be the trend of the future.','談到青少年偶像，第一個想到的不外乎是當紅藝人或是體育明星，但在網路時代可不一定。隨著網路速度的提升與資訊設備的進步，任何人都可以錄製影片上傳到網路上，一夕成名。以YouTube的頻道訂閱數來看，2014年金曲獎最佳國語男歌手林俊傑從2006年至今，共有36萬訂閱人數；而一位大學畢業兩年、網路暱稱叫做「魚乾」的女性遊戲實況玩家，她在3年內就獲得超過50萬人訂閱。然而，這些所謂的「實況主」，是否真的這麼輕鬆就能賺進大把鈔票？又是不是任何人都可以把打電動當職業呢?\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n以魚乾最常實況的遊戲《當個創世神》為例，這款遊戲是以獲取礦物與資源，打造自己的房屋、農田、城堡，並探索廣大的未知世界的遊戲。由於沒有劇情，如果實況主只是隨興閒逛，觀眾便會失去興趣。魚乾不但自己創造遊戲情節，甚至還透過留言系統，請網友寫下希望魚乾在遊戲裡面完成的事，並隨機抽選出三篇網友的留言，做為下一次挑戰的目標。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n這系列的挑戰影片總共10集，網友共提出30個千奇百怪的任務，讓魚乾花了將近一年的時間才挑戰完成。遊戲裡面最珍貴的礦物是鑽石，有一位網友留言的任務不但要魚乾挖到鑽石，而且還要把鑽石丟到岩漿裡。魚乾花了將近一個小時才挖到鑽石，然後就立刻將它丟棄了，「當下真是欲哭無淚啊！」魚乾說，雖然過程很痛苦，但成功增加觀眾互動程度，也是獲得YouTube年度最佳創意獎的理由之一。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n實況主的特殊才能，甚至還可以發展成副業。擁有一副好歌喉的魚乾，在實況中，常常有觀眾點歌，好歌聲也讓她在去年與朋友合作推出單曲，在網路上創造300萬次點閱次數，高過許多職業歌手；另一位人氣實況主「亞洲統神」，則因為其誇張、辛辣的說話方式，受到觀眾喜愛，而獲邀擔任許多電競賽事的轉播，成為重要的收入來源。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n在有了一定的知名度後，實況主也會接到許多廠商合作的機會，例如新遊戲試玩、商品試用、遊戲平台宣傳等；有些實況主甚至會獲電腦硬體廠商出資贊助，或是成立團隊，提高開台頻率，同時多角化經營自己的事業。','When asked about kids’ idols, most of us will think of celebrities or sports stars. However, in the age of the Internet, that’s no longer a sure thing. With the speed and power of modern broadband technology, anyone can upload their own videos to the Internet and become an overnight sensation. For example, Singaporean popstar JJ Lin, winner of the 2014 Golden Melody Award for Best Mandarin Male Singer, has accrued 360,000 subscribers to his You Tube channel since 2006; meanwhile a young woman two years out of college known only as “Annie” has, in her three years running a gaming channel, gathered more than 500,000 subscribers. However, is it really so easy for these “streamers” to rake in the big bucks? Can anyone just start a job playing video games?\r\n\r\nLook at the game Annie most frequently plays for streaming, Mine craft. The game is about collecting minerals and resources to build your own house, farm and castle, and exploring an vast and unknown world. Its lack of a plot means there’s freedom to do whatever you want, but if streamers do that, they risk losing the interest of their viewers. For that reason, Annie has not only created her own plot, but also set up a system for viewers to leave messages for her, from which she chooses three at random to decide what challenge to tackle next.\r\n\r\nOver the course of ten episodes and almost a full year, Annie took on 30 of the weird and wonderful suggestions made by her viewers. One such proposition was that Annie should not only seek out some of the most valuable mineral in the game, diamond, but that she should then throw it all into lava, destroying it. After almost an hour, she finally struck diamond, and then immediately went and dumped it into nearby lava. “I felt like I wanted to cry,” she said, but that momentary pain successfully boosted her interaction with viewers, and ultimately became one of the contributing factors to her winning her You Tube Best Creativity award.\r\n\r\nSome streamers are even able to translate their most important traits into side work. Annie, for example, has an excellent singing voice, and when she does live streams, she often gets requests from the audience. Last year, she and some friends worked together to release a single, and got over 3 million hits on You Tube, more than many professional singers. Another popular streamer, “Asia god”, has earned fans for his exaggerated, forthright way of speaking, and has even been asked to be a commentator on several e-sports competitions, creating a healthy source of income.\r\n\r\nOnce streamers have reached a level of recognition, they can then use that to create opportunities to work with sponsors, doing things like showcasing new games and products or promoting new gaming platforms. Some streamers even get sponsorships from hardware manufacturers or set up their own teams to help boost the frequency of their videos, as well as work on diversifying their careers.',0,'2021-02-24 18:53:17',NULL,NULL),
(5,5,'接續傳譯(英譯中)	','So today I\'m gonna share with you some speechwriter secrets. I don\'t know whether you know this, but there is a secret language of leadership; a secret language of leadership that we all used to be taught at school. Ancient rhetoric. This was a core part of the curriculum in Ancient Rome, part of the trivium.\r\n\r\nIn London, right the way through to the 19th century, it was possible to get a free education in rhetoric, but not in mathematics, reflecting the importance that was placed on the topic.\r\n\r\nToday, teaching in rhetoric is restricted; restricted to a powerful, privileged few. So what I\'m gonna do in my speech is revive this ancient art of rhetoric and share with you six techniques so that you can all speak like leaders.\r\n\r\n\r\nSo right, okay, stop. Right, stop listen. Look left, look right, look center. How are you feeling? Distressed? Anxious? Little bit edgy?\r\n\r\nThat\'s because I\'m mimicking hyperventilating. This is the authentic sound of fear, and that fear transfers to you. This is an ancient Roman rhetorical device; they used to call it asyndeton.\r\n\r\nAnd it\'s one leaders still use today. So David Cameron uses it: \"Broken homes, failing schools, sink estates.\" Tony Blair used to use it as well: \"Education, education. education.\" \r\n\r\nBarack Obama too: \"A world at war, a planet in peril, the worst financial crisis in a generation. Why three? Well, three is the magic number in rhetoric. \"Government of the people, by the people, for the people.\"\r\n(In German) \"One people, one empire, one leader.\"\r\n\r\nThis is also an ancient Roman rhetorical device. They used to call it tricolon, which makes it sound like a peculiar part of the digestive system. But it\'s just putting things in threes. You put your argument in threes, it makes it sound more compelling, more convincing, more credible. Just like that.\r\n\r\n\r\nLet\'s move on; number two. Three sentences in which the opening clause is repeated. Now this is what Winston Churchill did with his, \"We shall fight on the beaches, we shall fight on the landing grounds, we shall fight on the fields and in the streets.\"\r\n\r\nOf course, he could have said this a whole lot quicker. But he wanted to communicate his emotion, so he repeated it. When we are emotional about things, our perspective distorts. And this then manifests in our speech. And so this is the authentic sound of passion.\r\n\r\nIt sweeps people away. And this is why this technique is used by slick salesmen and by market traders. \"I\'m not asking £20, I\'m not asking £15, I\'m not even asking 10 pounds.\"\r\n\r\nIt sweeps people onto the next point, which is free balance in statements. \"Ask not what your country can do for you, ask what you can do for your country.\" \"There is nothing wrong with America that can\'t be cured by what\'s right with America.\"\r\n\r\n\"To be or not to be.\" If the sentence sounds as if it\'s balanced, we imagine that the underlying thinking is balanced, and our brain is tuned to like things that are balanced. Balanced minds, balanced diets, balanced lives.\r\n\r\nAnd so we are drawn to these kinds of sentences, we are attracted to them even if that balance is actually just an illusion. Like, we\'re looking to the future, not the past. We\'re working together, not against one another. We\'re thinking about what we can do, not what we can\'t.\r\n\r\nNow let\'s move on to number four. Metaphor. Metaphor is probably the most powerful piece of political communication.\r\nBut it\'s the bit no one ever talks about, the elephant in the room, so to speak, which is extraordinary.\r\n \r\nBecause we use metaphor once every 16 words on average. So our conversation is littered with metaphors, scattered with metaphors. We can\'t speak for very long without reaching for a metaphor, and metaphors are very loaded.\r\n\r\nSee, metaphors are all over the place, and they are political in that they are used by people to lead people towards things, or indeed to make them recoil.\r\n\r\nAnd so we use beautiful images, images of people, images of love, images of family, of sunshine, in order to draw people towards things,\r\n\r\nand we use disgusting images- vermin, scary monsters, disease, sickness, in order to make people recoil.','今天我將要與你分享一些演講稿寫手的秘密。我不知道你是不是知道這個，但是有一個領導的語言秘密。這個領導語言秘密是我們過去學校經常教導的。古代修辭學。這是古羅馬三學科中，最核心的一部分課程。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n在倫敦，直到１９世紀，我們很可能接受免費的修辭學教育，而不是數學，這反映出修辭學當日的重要性。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n時至今日，修辭學教育是給少數人的，只限於有權力的、有特權的少數幾個人。所以我將會在我接下來的演講中做的事情是，復甦這個古代修辭學藝術，並且和你們分享６個技巧，使你們全都可以像領導人那樣子演說。\r\n\r\n那麼，暫停。好，停下來聆聽。看左，看右，看中間。你覺得怎樣？哀傷？焦慮？有點急躁？\r\n\r\n\r\n這是因為我正在模仿呼吸過度。這是恐懼的真實聲音，而這個恐懼傳到你那邊。這就是古羅馬的修辭學工具。他們稱之為「接續詞省略」。\r\n\r\n\r\n這是一個領導人還在使用的技巧。所以卡梅倫使用：「破碎的家園，失敗的學校，陷落的家產。」貝理雅也使用了：「教育，教育，教育。」\r\n\r\n\r\n奧巴馬也是：「在戰爭中的世界，在苦難中的星球，一個世代中最慘的經濟危機。」為什麼是三呢？因為在修辭學，三是個魔術數字。「政府是民有，民治，民享。」、（德語）「一個人，一個帝國，一個領導人。」\r\n\r\n這也是古羅馬修辭學中的工具。他們過去稱之為「三迴轉」，聽起來像是消化系統的某個特別部位，但是它僅僅是將東西三個三個放在一起。你將論述以三為單位放在一起，這使得論述聽起來更矚目，更有說服力，更可信。就像這樣。\r\n\r\n我們繼續吧！第二。三個句子當中，第一個句子一直重複述說。現在，這是邱吉爾說過的，「我們將在沙灘戰鬥；我們將在降落地上戰鬥；我們將在田野和街道上戰鬥。」\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n當然，他可以把這整句話說快一點。但是他想傳達他的情緒，所以他重複了這句話。當我們對某件事情充滿情緒，我們的觀點會扭曲，這就反映在我們的談吐上。所以這是熱情的真實聲音。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n這橫掃人心。這也是為什麼這個技巧常被狡猾的商人、市集貿易商使用。「我不賣２０英磅，我不賣１５英磅，我甚至不賣１０英磅。」\r\n\r\n它把人們帶到下個論點，這是敘述中的自由平衡。「別問國家能為你做什麼，問你能為國家做什麼。」、「美國沒有什麼缺點，是不能被美國的優點補足的。」\r\n\r\n「做或者不做。」如果句子聽起來像是平衡的，我們就會把背後的思想想像成平衡的。我們的大腦本來就喜歡平衡的東西。平衡的心思，平衡的飲食，平衡的生活。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n所以我們被拉到這些句子當中。我們被這些句子吸引，甚至這些平衡的東西只是假象。像是「我們在找的是未來，而不是過去。」、「我們在一起工作，而不是彼此對抗。」、「我們在思考我們可以做的事，而不是不可以做的事。」\r\n\r\n\r\n現在我們繼續說第四個技巧。暗喻。暗喻可能是政治語言中，最有力量的一部分。但是這是從來沒人說過的，也就是說在房間裡的一頭大象，非常特別。\r\n\r\n\r\n因為我們平均每１６個字詞就會使用一次暗喻。所以我們的交談中，摻雜了暗喻，遍布了暗喻。我們如果不尋求一個暗喻，就不能說得太久，而且暗喻都寓意深長。\r\n\r\n\r\n看吧！暗喻無所不在，而且有政治意味，人們用來帶領人們贊成某些事務，或者實在是使他們畏懼。\r\n\r\n\r\n所以我們使用美麗的圖像，人的圖像，愛的圖像，家庭的圖像，陽光的圖像，去吸引人們贊成某些事務。\r\n\r\n\r\n而我們使用噁心的圖像：害蟲、可怕的怪獸、病害、疾病，使人們退縮。','And today I want to show you two fun ways to practice English doing things you already\r\nlove to do. Okay? So, let\'s go to the board. Mr. E is saying: \"I sound like Madonna!\" That\'s not here yet, but that\'ll be the second one, but today or right now this part of the lesson is about movies, acting.\r\n\r\nWhat we want you to do or what I want you to do is go find a movie you love in English. I\'m sure there\'s... If you\'re watching me, I\'m sure you\'ve watched some English television program or movie. I mean, I\'m speaking a lot of English so I know you\'re used to it.\r\n\r\nWhat I... What I want you to do is pretend you are an actor in a movie, and we\'re going to take a few steps to get there. So the first thing is: Pick a movie that you love watching, because some of you watch it again and again. Star Wars, yeah, yeah? Or Harry Potter, if that\'s still out there, or Bond, James Bond. Right? Any of those movies. Okay, so you pick your movie.\r\n\r\nThe second thing I want you to do is go through the movie and watch the scenes you love the best when the actor says something like: \"Punk, do you feel lucky, punk? Well, do ya?\" And then pick a couple of those scenes. All right?\r\n\r\nThe third thing I want you to do is go to this part, and it\'s i-m... It\'s www.imsdb.com. It\'s where you get scripts. Now, right now you\'re probably going: \"What\'s a script?\" Well, in music the words in the music are called lyrics. Okay? So when you\'re looking at the words in a song they\'re called the lyrics.\r\n\r\nBut when you\'re looking at the words in a movie, it\'s from a script. And one actor has his part in a script, another actor has her part in a script. And these are the lines they say.\r\n\r\nThis particular website has amazing amount... An amazing amount of movies with scripts, so you can go and find any of the latest ones, like of Jason Bourne, or I\'m trying to think of something that came out.\r\nI don\'t know when you\'re going to see this, so just say Harry Potter, maybe Ironman. Okay? Go check it out, you\'ll see the scripts, you can go and look at it.\r\n\r\nThe reason why I asked you up here is to pick out scenes is you can go to the scene on the script where it may say: \"Car chase scene\", \"Gun scene\", \"Kissing scene\", and you can look at it, and all of the words the actors say are there. Because I know sometimes you don\'t know what the actor is actually saying.\r\n\r\nSometimes we have what\'s called relaxed speech. In relaxed speech, they might say: \"What do you want?\" and it comes out: \"Whatda ya want?\" And you\'re like: \"What?\" It\'s English. Now, we have a video on relaxed speech, you can go and check it out, and it will explain: \"Whatda ya want?\" and other ones. Okay?\r\n\r\nSo, the lines that will be there, you might notice a big difference between what the actor says and what is actually written for what you should explain or you should understand. Okay? This is good, it\'s going to help you with your ears as well. There\'s a thing you can pick up from listening. Okay? So we want to look at the scripts and then listen.\r\n\r\nNow, watch the movie at your favourite part. So now you\'ve got the script in your hand, you\'re going to watch that part. Read. Here\'s the funny thing, a lot of times people read when they\'re watching a movie, like they read the subtitles-you know the little words?-and they think: \"My listening is good because I understand.\" No, you\'re reading, but it does help because it helps you put a picture, a word picture to the words you\'re hearing. And we\'re much better with pictures.\r\n\r\nThink of it this way: Have you ever walked up to someone and said: \"I remember your name, but I don\'t remember your face.\" No, you don\'t do that. We always remember faces and we forget names. Those kind of words and sounds are hard to remember, but the picture we always keep.\r\n\r\nSeeing a word picture or a word \"dog\" and then seeing a dog is easier to remember dog and the picture of the dog together. So now you get to look at the words, and see them, and see the person saying it. It\'s easier for you to remember, or another word is recall. \r\n\r\nOkay? So watch that a couple of times. Watch how they say it, watch their mouths and read the words. Try to get it at the same speed so as you\'re reading, they\'re talking. Cool? \r\n\r\nNow, here\'s the fun part. I want you to repeat the script with the movie. So if we were doing this now, if I were saying: \"How are you, brown cow?\" You would be reading: \"How are you, brown cow?\" and you try and copy me. So if I went: \"How are you, brown cow?\" you\'d have to say: \"How are you, brown cow? How are you, brown cow? How are you, brown cow?\" And so you can match me.\r\n\r\nThe funny thing about trying to copy someone is that you stop thinking in your language, and as you\'re trying to copy your accent will drop off, especially when you\'re trying to match their speed. And you\'ll notice that your accent is gone and you sound more like an American, or an Englishman, or I don\'t know, a person from Vietnam.\r\n\r\nBe careful which language you pick. I might say: Pick American/British actors first. You don\'t want to sound like a Russian. Okay? Russian is very good, I like them a lot, they\'re good people, but if you\'re trying to learn English accent like American, it\'s not good way to start. Okay? So after you get good at the English and Americans, then pick your French accent. Yes, you can be a lover. Or an Italian accent. But first, English and American.\r\n\r\nOkay? So try and match the speed and the way that the other speaker or the actor is speaking. Okay? Now, copy the actor as much as possible, maybe even a gesture, because sometimes using your hands... Like when some people, they talk like this, they start acting like... And the accent comes out because they know it\'s a different culture. I know it\'s crazy, but just try it. It\'s fun. What\'s the worst that can happen? You watch your favourite movie.\r\n\r\nNow, there are a couple of things I want to talk about very quickly on this. Number one, share the fun. You can have a friend get another part of the movie and you can talk to each other. \"Hey, Johnny, what\'s going on?\" \"Yeah, Beany, I haven\'t seen you in a while.\" \"Johnny, I told you, don\'t call me B-...\" See? And you can have fun together. Laugh, watch a movie, have some fun, work on your English, getting rid of that accent. Okay? Cool?\r\n\r\nAnd the second thing is: Look for language or I say sound patterns. \"Whatda ya\" is \"What do you?\" How we have some words that have certain patterns that are repeated again and again. By watching the movie again and again, that part, you\'ll start learning these sound patterns and you\'ll notice you don\'t have to say each word. \r\n\r\nHow do I know you\'re not a native English speaker? You say to me: \"What are you doing, teacher?\" instead of: \"Whatda ya doing, teacher?\" See? A sound pattern. And you can take that: \"Whatda ya\" for many things. Cool? All right. I promised you one fun way, and I\'m sure you\'re enjoying watching your movie.','今天我想告訴你兩種有趣的練習英文的方法。你可以做些你已經喜歡的事情，就能學好英文。OK？所以請看白板吧。E先生說：「我聽起來就像麥當娜！」還沒到這堂課，這會是下一堂，此時此刻這是堂關於電影、表演的課。\r\n\r\n\r\n我想請你們做的事就是找一部你喜歡的英文電影。我敢說⋯⋯ 如果你在收看我的視頻，我敢說你應該會看一些英文電視節目或是電影。我意思是我講那麼多英文，我知道你已經習慣了聽英文。\r\n\r\n而我想要你做的事情是我想請你假裝你是一位電影裡的角色，我們需要幾個步驟讓你變成那個角色。第一件事：選一部你喜歡的電影，因為你們其中一些人一定會不斷一看再看。星球大戰，對吧？ 或是哈利波特，如果那還有的話，或是占士邦，對吧？ 任何電影都行。OK，所以你選電影。\r\n\r\n\r\n第二件事，我想請你看完這部電影，然後看看你最喜歡的幾個鏡頭，像是演員可能會說：「廢物，你覺得你很幸運嗎？ 廢物，嗯？」然後挑選幾幕。好。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n第三件事我想請你到這地方，就是www.imsdb.com。你可以在那取得腳本。這時候，你可能在想：「什麼是腳本？」在音樂中的字稱為歌詞，OK？所以當你看到歌曲中的字，那些稱為歌詞。\r\n\r\n\r\n但當你看到電影當中的字幕，那就是從腳本來的。一個演員在腳本中會有自己的戲分，另一個演員也有，這些就是他們說的台詞。\r\n\r\n這個特別網站⋯⋯有數量非常龐大的電影腳本，所以你可以找到任何最近的電影，像是叛諜追擊，或是其他我試著想到的電影。我不知道你是什麼時候會看我這部影片，所以我就舉哈利波特為例，或是鐵甲奇俠吧，OK？去看看，你會看到很多腳本，可以點進去瞧瞧。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我在這裡跟你說選幾幕鏡頭的原因，就是你可以去看這幾幕的腳本，或許會有：快車追逐、槍戰、吻戲的場景，然後你可以在那看看演員講的所有台詞，因為我知道有時候你其實不知道演員在講什麼。\r\n\r\n有時我們會稱之為閒聊。在閒聊時，他們可能會說：「What do you want?」那聽起來會是「Whatda ya want?」然後你就會想說：「什麼？」但那就是英文。現在，我們有閒聊的影片，你可以去瞧瞧，它會解釋: 「Whatda ya want?」 還有其他的台詞，OK？\r\n\r\n\r\n所以那裡的台詞，你可能會注意到演員講出的，和實際上寫出來你所了解的台詞有很大的差異，OK？這樣很好，因為這對你的聽力也有幫助。你可以藉聽力來學習，OK？所以我們會看著腳本然後聽。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n現在，去觀賞一部電影中你最喜歡的部分。你手上有腳本，你會去觀賞那幾幕鏡頭，讀腳本。有件有趣的事，很多時候人們看電影時會閱讀，他們會讀字幕，就是那些小字，然後就會想：「我的聽力不錯耶，因為都聽得懂」不對，你那是在閱讀，但那也有幫助，因為它幫助你透過視覺，去連接你所聽到的。我們對於視覺擅長多了。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n試著想：你試過走向某個人，說：「我記得你的名字，但我不記得你的長相。」嗎？不會的，你不會那樣做，我們都是記住長相，卻忘記名字。那些字和音總是很難記，但我們都會記住影像。\r\n\r\n\r\n看到一個「dog」文字描述或單字，再去看一隻狗，會更容易連同影像一起記憶。你看到那些字，看到它們，然後看到講這些字的人。對你來說，這會更容易記憶，或是回憶起。\r\n\r\nOK？所以多看幾次吧。看看他們是怎麼說的，看看他們的嘴型然後讀出那些詞。試著讓你的閱讀和他們的講話速度一樣，可以嗎？\r\n\r\n\r\n再來就是有趣的部分了。我希望你可以跟著電影覆誦出腳本台詞。如果我們現在就來試一次，我說：「How are you, brown cow?」你就讀：「How are you, brown cow?」然後你試著模仿我。我會說：「How are you, brown cow?」你就說：「How are you, brown cow? How are you, brown cow? How are you, brown cow?」然後你就會跟我一樣了。\r\n\r\n\r\n模仿別人有趣的地方，就在於你會停止用自己的語言思考。當你正試著模仿，自己的口音就會不見，尤其是當你試著要跟上他們的速度時。然後會發現你的口音沒了，你講起來更像美國人或是英國人，或是，我不知道，來自越南的人吧。\r\n\r\n\r\n要小心你選的語言。我可能會建議：先選英美的演員。你不會希望聽起來像是俄國口音，OK？俄國人很好，我很喜歡他們，他們人很好，但當你是要學美國人的口音，那不會是個好的開始，OK？所以當你學會了英式和美式，你可以挑選法國口音，你可以變成一位戀人，或是義大利口音。但首先，選英式和美式的。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nOK？試著跟上速度和其他講者或是演員說話的方式，OK？盡可能的模仿演員，甚至是手勢，因為有時用你的手⋯⋯像是有些人講話會這樣，他們開始演⋯⋯然後口音就會出來，因為他們知道這是不同的文化。我知道這很瘋狂，但就嘗試看看吧。很有趣的，最糟能怎麼樣？你在看你喜歡的電影。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n現在，我有幾件事想很快的說。第一，分享樂趣。你可以找個朋友演另一個部分，你們可以彼此對話。「嘿，Jonny，最近如何啊？」「還不錯，Beany，有段時間沒見到你了。」「Johnny，我說過不要叫我B⋯⋯」看到嗎？你們可以一起享受樂趣。大笑，看電影，找些樂趣，努力練英文，去掉你的口音，不錯吧？\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n然後第二： 找一些語言或是我說的發音模式。「Whatda ya」就是「What do you?」有些字是怎麼不斷運用特定的模式來說。你可以透過重複看電影開始學習這些發音模式，然後就會發現你不需要講出每一個單字。\r\n\r\n\r\n我是怎麼知道英文不是你的母語？你會跟我說：「What are you doing, teacher?」而不是說：「Wharda ya doing, teacher?」對吧？發音模式。你可以用「Whatda ya」講很多東西，可以嗎？好了，我保證你有一種有趣的方法，而你現在一定很享受看自己喜歡的電影。',0,'2021-02-24 18:54:29',NULL,NULL),
(6,6,'接續傳譯(中譯英)	','46歲的阿傑中四畢業後當上酒店房務員，在酒店業任職20多年。他希望轉行\r\n在飲食業發展，因為缺乏相關經驗，所以報讀僱員再培訓局茶餐廳廚吧助理基礎證書課程，自我增值，尋找新出路。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n阿傑說，課程加深對飲食業認識，增強個人自信。他相信畢業後，有助自己在茶餐廳找到工作。\r\n\r\n\r\n聖雅各福群會是其中一個開辦這課程的培訓機構，讓學員掌握基本茶餐廳運作和實務技能，包括沖茶技巧、各類茶餐的製作和配搭、各式扒類和小食製作等。\r\n\r\n從事飲食行業30年的導師袁振威說，在茶餐廳工作看似簡單，其實一點也不容易，就像沖一杯香滑奶茶 ，步驟相當講究。\r\n\r\n\r\n「水滾茶靚，先沖茶，後加奶，便可鑑定茶水的顏色和味道，所以我會教學員\r\n先沖茶，後加奶。\r\n\r\n\r\n「整個課程180小時，大部分時間內容均為實務，讓學員多接觸實務，能夠增加信心，熟能生巧。我認為喜歡飲食的人士投身這行業會事半功倍。」\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n除了想轉行，課程同樣吸引待業人士報讀。50歲的阿敏是家庭主婦，兩名子女長大後，想再工作，於是報讀茶餐廳廚吧助理基礎證書課程，畢業後在一間飯堂當兼職廚吧助理，主要負責分配菜色和水吧工作。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n聖雅各福群會每年平均開辦三班茶餐廳廚吧助理基礎證書課程，逾八成學員年齡介乎40至69歲，最近三年畢業學員就業率約八成。','Ah Kit, 46, who worked as a hotel room attendant since completing secondary four more than two decades ago, had decided to switch to a career in the catering industry. Without relevant experience, he joined the Local Cafe Kitchen Assistant Training course, an Employees Retraining Board programme.\r\n\r\nKit has gained both knowledge in the catering industry and a new sense of confidence. He feels the programme will help him find a job in a local cafe.\r\n\r\nSt James’ Settlement is one of the trainers for the programme. Students learn a wide range of skills, from the intricacies of operating a restaurant to the art of brewing the perfect cuppa. \r\n\r\n\r\nMr. Yuen Chun-wai, who has worked in the catering industry for three decades, is one of the course’s instructors. He said working in a local cafe is not an easy task. For instance, it takes much skill to make milk tea.\r\n\r\n“Boiling water and quality tea is the key. I teach my students to add milk after they make the tea. This way the tea will have the optimal texture in both colour and taste.”\r\n\r\n“The course takes about 180 hours to complete and enhances the students’ technical skills as well as brushes up their confidence through hands-on learning. I believe that culinary aficionados will do well in catering careers.”\r\n\r\n\r\nThe course is also helping the unemployed join the workforce. Fifty-year-old housewife Ah Man wanted to return to work now that her kids have grown up.  She decided to join the Local Cafe Kitchen Assistant Training course last year. She is now working as a part-time kitchen assistant in a canteen, mainly for food and drink preparation.\r\n\r\nSt James’ Settlement runs about three courses a year. More than 80% of its students are aged between 40 and 69. The employment rate of its graduates was about 80% in the past three years. ','當一個醫生有辦法去改變生老病死嗎？坦白講，很困難。當一個醫生，只是讓人在生老病死之間活得好看一點，就這樣而已。所以慢慢的我想通一個道理，醫師只是生命花園的園丁。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n但是，醫師是個生命花園的園丁，面對草木的枯榮，他到底要怎麼去面對，所以作為一個重症醫學的專家，我如何去面對死亡。就死亡的科學觀來講，如果從物理化學來講，一切的物理反應，物理化學反應，應該是最低能量最大亂度，所謂的Delta S要大於等於零。\r\n\r\n\r\n當然有人說Delta S大於零到底怎麼來的，有人認為是大爆炸理論，因為大爆炸理論，整個宇宙在擴充，所以Delta S會大於零，或是這樣，宇宙定理到底有沒有恆一性，坦白講，我也不知道，所以有一句話：夏蟲不可語冬雪，就是說，夏天的蟲沒有辦法講冬天的事情，因為他活不了那麼久。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n到底宇宙的物理有沒有恆一性，在無限的空間和時間當中，有沒有恆一性，坦白講，我不知道，但是至少在我們可以感受的範圍內，Delta S還是大於零。什麼叫Delta S大於零呢，理論上，一切要最低能量最大亂度，越來越混亂，所以我的存在Delta小於零，他是違反整個物理化學的反應。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n那如何看待生死，其寶是這樣，我們常常只看到我，沒有看到我們是個宇宙，我加上環境才是個宇宙，所以Delta S total 是Delta S system 加 Delta S surrounding，所以這是個很重要的概念，任何有組織的團體，他都是不穩定的，他必須破壞環境，所以雖然Delta S小於零，但是我要破壞整個環境，讓Delta S大於零，加起來還是要大於零。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n所以我的存在就是要破壞這個環境。當有一天我再也不能破壞這個環境的時候，我只好破壞我自己，因為我還是要維持Delta S大於零。所以存在之目的是為了破壞，當不能再破壞時，只好破壞自己，這個叫死亡。這是從物理化學的觀點來看待死亡。\r\n\r\n可是做一個醫生，物理化學我懂，可是如果去看待人生呢？有一天我在加護病房，在巡房時突然大徹大悟，人生的結局只有兩種，一個有插管，一個沒插管，但是都是死掉。所以死亡是個普遍存在的現象。那到底我們如何看待死亡呢？\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n其實這個問題我有個翻轉的想法。你問我什麼叫死亡，我如此的回答：怎樣才算是活着？所以今天各位來這裏聽演講，我希望你們回家以後，今天晚上睡覺的時候，躺在床上問自己一個問題：怎樣才算是活着？\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n因為怎樣才算是活着，我們要思考一個問題，什麼是人生？我對這個問題的答案是這樣：追求這個問題的答案就是這個問題的答案。因為人一定會死，沒有人會把死亡當作人生的目的，所以人生只是個過程。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n因此這個過程當中，我們在這個過程當中，不斷去追尋一個問題：到底什麼才叫做活着，所以追求這個問題的答案，就是這個問題的答案。所以死亡不應當作是人生的目的，人生只是個過程。\r\n\r\n最近我常常去講一坨大便的啟示。有一次我的老師退休，就跟我說，老師要退休了，請好一點的。我說好啦好啦，我就跟我的學長和老師，到喜來登飯店二樓安東廳法國餐廳，三個人吃了26,000塊。\r\n\r\n\r\n我看到賬單時，臉都綠掉了，我怎麼吃這麼貴的東西，因為我也沒去過那種地方，亂點，也不曉得點了什麼菜，所以看到賬單的時候， 26,000塊。我第二天早上上廁所，一直看我的大便。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我在想，這個花9,000元才製造出來的東西，我看來看去，跟我平常在台大醫院地下室一樓自助餐70塊的，我看不出差別。我在廁裏面突然大徹大悟，人生的榮華富貴，不過就是一坨大便。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n儒家還是中國最重要的思想，可是儒家他的優點，他把人提升到一個境界，可是你看看《論語》怎麼講，《論語》裏面說：未知生，焉知死？未能事人，焉能事鬼。生，事之以禮；死，葬之以禮，祭之以禮。他就是不想談論生死，你一直追問，他就說什麼是捨生取義，朝聞道，夕死可矣，什麼有殺身以成仁。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n這個儒家對生死的態度，他採取一種逃避的態度，他不想討論，所以他積極面當然是要人，要就是不要管他，管你現在的東西就好，可是有一個問題，他躲避了死亡的問題。我的想法是這樣，在這個中華文化圈裏，儒家還是中國最重要的思想，可是過去我們都不想面對生死，採取逃避的態度。\r\n\r\n這是我個人的看法，置於死地而後生，我們唯有能夠面對死亡，甚至開始凝視死亡的時候，才能轉過來看人生到底是什麼。所以人生終究會死亡，人生只是個過程，只是追求人生意義的過程，這是我個人的感想。','As a doctor, am I capable of changing natures rules to birth, ageing, sickness or death? Well, it is very difficult. As a doctor, all we can do is to enable people to go through life a little easier when they are alive. That’s all. So gradually, I came to realise that doctors are just the gardeners in the life’s garden. \r\n\r\nAs a Gardener, when faced with the withered plants, how to treat them is a great question. As an expert in critical care, how do I face death? From a scientific aspect, or from molecular science, a system undergoing molecular reaction will tend to minimise energy and maximise entropy. So Delta S should be greater or equal to 0. \r\n\r\n\r\nSomebody asked how Delta S is greater than zero. Some believe it’s from the big bang theory, as it describes the state of ever-expanding universe. So that’s how Delta S is greater than zero. Is anything constant in the laws of the universe? Honestly, I don’t have an answer to this. So there’s an old saying “a blind man is no judge of colours.” Visually impaired folks can’t distinguish colours so it’s pointless to ask them to judge. \r\n\r\nDoes constant apply to the laws in this universe? Does it exist in this eternal space and time? Frankly, I don’t have these answers. But at least, within the realm of our knowledge, Delta S is still positive. What does it mean when we say Delta S is positive? In theory, objects tend to be in minimum energy and maximum entropy, creating greater disorder. My existence would be in a Delta S less than zero, which defies molecular science. \r\n\r\nThen how should we view life and death? Actually, we often see ourselves only. We don’t realise that we are in the universe. The universe is the combination of us and the environment. So Delta S total equals to Delta S system and Delta S surrounding. So this is an important concept. Any organised group is always in an unstable state. The group disrupts its surrounding. So even if Delta S for the group is negative, because the group disrupts its surrounding, Delta S total is greater than zero to make the equation positive. \r\n\r\nSo my existence is to disrupt my surrounding until one day when I can no longer do so, that’s when I disrupt myself so Delta S total can remain positive. In essence, our existence is to disrupt. When you’re unable to disrupt the surrounding, you end up disrupting yourself. It’s death from a molecular science aspect. \r\n\r\nHowever, as a doctor, I understand molecular science. But what about the meaning of life? One day, when I was in ICU making my rounds, I came to realise That humans only have two types of ending. One is with inserted tubes. The other is without. Both represent death. This is every person’s final journey. So what does death mean to us？ \r\n\r\nI’d like to share a contrasting viewpoint on this. If you ask me what death is, I will ask you: what does it mean to be alive? Everyone here in this audience came to hear a lecture. I hope you can do one thing when you leave. Before falling asleep tonight, when you’re lying on your bed, ask yourself this question: “What does it mean to be alive?” \r\n\r\nBecause this question leads us to contemplate on the meaning of life. My answer to the question is this: “When you’re searching for the answer to the question, it is the answer to the question.” Everyone dies eventually. No one will set death as his or her goal in life. Therefore, life is just a process. \r\n\r\nIn this process, during one’s entire lifespan, we keep searching for the answer to the meaning of existence. So when you’re searching for the answer to existence, that is the very answer to the question. So death is not the goal of life. Life is just a process. \r\n\r\nRecently, I’ve been sharing the story of faeces. My teacher was going to retire. He said, “I am going to retire, treat me to something fancy.” I said of course. So my teacher, schoolmate and I went to the Sheraton to celebrate in a French restaurant. The three of us spent 26,000 dollars. \r\n\r\nI was astonished when I got the bill. How could I eat something so expensive? I’d never been to the restaurant before. We ordered some random unknown dishes. When I saw the bill, 26,000 dollars, I was too shocked to speak. The next morning, in the toilet, I examined my faeces carefully. \r\n\r\nI thought I’d spent 9,000 dollars producing this. After careful examination, I concluded that this poo looks the same as what is produced after a meal in the NTU hospital cafeteria which costs 70 dollars. I couldn’t tell the difference. In the toilet I came to realise that all the wealth one desires turns out to be nothing more than crap. \r\n\r\nConfucianism is the most important philosophical system in China. The advantages of Confucianism are that its philosophy is about human virtues. Let’s take a look at the Analects of Confucius. “How does one understand death if one does not even know how to live?” “While alive, one must respect others; so that upon death, one’s body will be respected.” Confucius refused to talk about life and death. Instead, Confucius gave answers to sacrificing life for justice and how man holds no regret when he understands “the way”. \r\n\r\nTo Confucius, death is a topic to be avoided. He wants no discussion. So the positive side of Confucianism philosophy is that it instead focuses on the present situation. But it fails to address the issue of death. The following is what I think. In Chinese culture, Confucianism is the most important philosophy. But we didn’t discuss life and death, evading the issue. \r\n\r\nThis is what I believe. There’s a saying from Sun Tzu’s Art of War: “Force solders to see the face of death and they will fight to stay alive”. Only when we are able to face death, or even begin contemplating death, that’s when we can reflect on what life is. We will all die one day. Life is just a process, a process of searching for the meaning of existence. That’s my own opinion. ',0,'2021-02-24 18:55:31',NULL,NULL),
(7,7,'即時傳譯(英譯中)	','Police will launch the e-Ticketing Pilot Scheme on March 16.\r\n\r\nThe scheme will give traffic wardens the ease of using a mobile application installed in official smartphones. All they have to do is simply scan the encrypted QR code on vehicle licences or input vehicle registration numbers to extract details of offending drivers’ vehicles. The mobile app will then generate necessary information automatically and traffic wardens can print fixed penalty tickets with portable printers.\r\n\r\nIn the old days, we had to handwrite all the required information in the fixed penalty tickets. That would create the chance of making many more human errors. Now, we use the QR code or vehicle registration number to extract the data from the system. The mobile app can also extract the date, time and location from the GPS. That would greatly minimise the chance of human errors.\r\n\r\nThe scheme will first be rolled out in Wan Chai, Tseung Kwan O and Sham Shui Po police districts to combat illegal parking.\r\n\r\nAbout 60 traffic wardens will use e-Ticketing initially.\r\n\r\nThe Transport Department will imprint encrypted QR codes on newly issued vehicle licences.	\r\n','警方3月16日起推行電子定額罰款通知書先導計劃。\r\n\r\n這個計劃讓交通督導員透過流動電話程式掃描行車證上的二維碼或輸入車牌號碼，程式會自動輸入車輛資料，然後交通督導員會以便攜式打印機列印告票。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n以前手寫定額罰款通知書，有機會經常寫錯，現時使用二維碼或車牌號碼匯入資料。新流動電話程式同時會從全球定位系統匯入日期、時間、地點，大大減少人手輸入的錯誤。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n計劃率先在灣仔、將軍澳和深水埗警區試行，打擊違例泊車。\r\n\r\n計劃初期有約60名交通督導員參與。\r\n\r\n\r\n運輸署將會在新發出的行車證加入二維碼。\r\n\r\n','Hello, my name is Jared. Today we\'re going \r\nto look at tips for job interviews in English.\r\n\r\nFirst, practice. You only get a few minutes to impress the interview panel, so make sure that you practice the answers to common interview questions. Ask a friend to play the role of interviewer. Answer the questions and get some feedback from your friend. Try again until you are happy with your responses.\r\n	\r\nNext, make sure that you research the company you are applying to. If you know someone who already works there, maybe you can ask them about working for the company. If you don\'t know anyone, you can do some online research to find out what kind of company they are. Also, research the latest developments in the relevant business area. This sort of information will really impress the interviewers and also show you have initiative.\r\n	\r\nOur next tip is to look the part. Appearances do matter in the job interview. It is important that you look smart and professional. Make sure that your clothes are appropriate. First appearances are important. Make sure that you smile and make eye contact with the interviewers. Don\'t forget to speak clearly and not too fast. Give yourself time to think about your responses.\r\n	\r\nLastly, don\'t forget to ask questions, too. This shows you\'re genuinely interested in the position and the company. Do ask questions about professional development and career prospect, for example.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re hoping to use English for a work, a Cambridge English business certificate could help you succeed. To find out more, visit our website. Good luck with getting that job. Thanks for watching.\r\n','哈囉，我是 Jared。今天要介紹英文面試工作的秘訣。\r\n\r\n首先，多練習。你只有幾分鐘的時間吸引面試官的目光，因此你必須確定自己能夠熟練地回答常見的面試問題。你可以請朋友扮演面試官的角色。回答問題，請朋友給你一些意見。反覆練習直到你滿意自己的回答為止。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n接著，你必須深入了解面試的公司。\r\n如果有認識的人在那裡工作，也許你可以向他們詢問在公司裡的工作狀況。\r\n如果你沒有認識的人，你可以上網搜尋，了解公司背景。除此之外，了解公司相關業務的最新發展。這些資訊會讓面試官印象深刻，同時也展現你積極進取的一面。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n下一個秘訣是注意你的服裝儀容。工作面試時，服裝儀容相當重要。要讓自己看起來聰明又專業。你必須確定自己穿著得體。第一印象十分重要。記得微笑並與面試官有眼神接觸。別忘了口齒要清晰，不要說得又快又急。給自己一點時間思考接下來的回答。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n最後，別忘了問問題。藉提問展現你對職務與公司有濃厚興趣。可以詢問有關專業發展與未來職涯相關的問題。\r\n\r\n\r\n如果你希望能從事英文專業相關的工作，劍橋商業英文證書可以幫助你成功。想了解更多，可以拜訪我們的網站。祝你順利獲聘。謝謝收看。\r\n',0,'2021-02-24 18:56:24',NULL,NULL),
(8,8,'即時傳譯(中譯英)	','天文台和國泰航空合作開發「我的航班天氣」流動應用程式，該應用程式已在國泰航空及國泰港龍航空的航班投入服務，有助兩家航空公司推行飛行文件無紙化計劃。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們是全球首個氣象當局開發類似程式，飛機師只要簡單輸入航班號碼，就可瀏覽航班所需資料，這要天文台與國泰合作才能做到。我們希望與其他航空公司繼續合作，基本上同一模式也可應用於其他航空公司。\r\n\r\n「我的航班天氣」流動應用程式提供最新氣象資訊，有機場天氣報告、機場天氣預測、危險天氣警告，並有天文台自行研發的全球湍流預報，有助提升飛行安全和效率。\r\n','MyFlightWx, an mobile application jointly developed by Hong Kong Observatory and Cathay Pacific, has commenced operation on both Cathay Pacific and Cathay Dragon flights. It will contribute to the two airlines\' paperless initiative. \r\n\r\nWe are the first observatory to develop this type of application. Simply enter the flight number and the pilot can browse all relevant information. This required collaboration between us and Cathay Pacific. We hope we can continue to work with other airlines using the same model.\r\n\r\nThe application provides the latest weather information, including airport weather reports, aerodrome forecasts and hazardous weather warnings, in addition to the global turbulence forecast developed solely by the Observatory, enhancing flight safety and efficiency. \r\n','基本上我今天所說的是一個關於搶錢和搶地的故事。大家看一看這幅圖，香港人從來都不特別關心農業，直至大概六七年前，我們有高鐵這件事，我們有保護菜園村事件，當時大家突然間發現，原來好像是香港還有很多人在耕田。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n這幅圖上可清楚看到，全香港大概有110,000公頃土地，其中有4,500公頃還是農地，這是說在政府規劃中，即漁農署官方數字還有4,500公頃，大概佔了全香港土地的4%，所以剛才的影片說了，大概等於220個維多利亞公園，其實是非常大的面積。但是你看到深綠色的4,000多公頃中，有人用於耕田大概是700公頃，即大概只有五分之一，少於五分之一還有人在耕田，為什麼有這個問題呢？我相信大家每天看新聞和政府論述都知道，香港農業已經式微，被市場慢慢淘汰。當然我不會完全否認，因為很簡單，我們每天吃的蔬菜，九成五以上都由大陸一車一車運來，但大家亦要留意，這4,000多公頃的所謂農地裏，其實起碼有1,500至2,000公頃已經被發展商所謂去囤積，例如在馬屎埔或古洞，在新界東北的範圍內，其實有很多農地已經被鐵絲網圍着，甚至有人耕種，發展商仍然在隔壁攔上鐵絲網。還有大家這幾天看新聞，有泥頭山，在天水圍，事實上絕大部分的農地，每日無時無刻都在給人在傾倒泥頭，即是說，對地主來說，那些是私人土地，用來傾倒泥頭也勝過租給你耕田，為什麼傾倒泥頭更加好？當然，當農地被破壞後，將來便有機會去改變用途，例如變成貨倉或起樓等等。所以這些都是香港農業不能發展的原因。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n最後看看上邊紅色的圈，很細的一個圈，大概是7至80公頃，是什麼意思呢？是一個香港的建議裏的農業泥頭山園，這是大概在一年多前政府出了一個新農業政策諮詢中，便建議我們用這樣一個農業園來支持香港的農業發展。你看看其實它佔我們香港實際上現有的法定農地是多少，其實大概是少於2%。其實我的關注重點不是這個80公頃的農業園究竟有沒有用，而是當政府劃了這80公頃之後，那麼圍着大圈的綠色有什麼用？為甚麼我們的農業園不是劃大些，而只是劃紅圈這麼小的地方呢？\r\n\r\n接着這幅圖是說所有農地，即是將剛才的圈放大了。我們香港的蔬菜自給率，以前我們在六七十年代，當我們的農業是最興盛的時候，我們的自給率可以達到五成以上。事實上，我們現在很多的農產品的自給率一點也不低，譬如有一種我們現在香港自產自銷的農產品，那個自給率仍然達到六成，不知大家會否猜到，其實便是活雞。如果你到街市買一隻活的雞劏呢，原來尚有六成在香港自己養的。即是說，如果我們是認真去做好農業，我們絕對有可能將自給率再次提高。以我剛才說的蔬菜為例，我們現在的自給率已經由五成以上跌至只剩1.9%，即是深綠色的圈，我們現在使用的土地種出的菜。但是如果我們用回4,000多公頃，全部活化，實際上我們的自給率可以達到三成甚至更高以上。大家是否覺得這是香港需要的呢？為什麼我們要自己種菜，為什麼我們不只是吃大陸菜？我相信越來越多人對於這個問題有一個更正面和積極的想法，就是我們真的需要自己種菜，無論是氣候轉變、全球暖化、很多地方越來越乾旱、沙漠化，你每年，現在三月是嗎？看看北京的新聞，沙塵暴等等，亦意味着這個糧食危機只會越來越惡化。\r\n\r\n新加坡的自給率指標，即是自己種菜給自己吃的指標是百分之十，我們比新加坡有更加大的優勢，我們有農地，我們可以達到三成甚至更加高，但是為什麼我們的農地不是用來種菜，是政府究竟正在打什麼算盤呢？簡單來說，我們在五六十年前，我們的農業是非常蓬勃的，在五十年代，我們有嘉道理基金會，即是現在的嘉道理農場，它是大力扶持一些農業發展，而當時事實上，對於當時的港英政府來說，第一，當然很多難民下來，即是我們的上一代，很需要有糧食，如果一旦沒有糧食，可能便會有亂；另外便是，大家也知道，當時剛剛解放，其實港英政府很怕共產黨的滲透，所以盡量釋放一些農地給新移民去自己種自己吃，或者是可以再賣出。所以如果大家有印象，譬如很簡單，有很多原居民，即是現在的新界原居民，在那個年代，其實是移民到英國、荷蘭開餐館，或在唐人街肯定有這些原居民你會找到，其實就是當時港英政府刻意把他們搬到英國，那真是一個正式的政策，然後騰空一些土地給當時的新移民種菜。\r\n','Basically, it is a story about snatching money and land. Please look at the picture. Hong Kong people are not particularly concerned about agriculture until six or seven years ago when we had the High Speed Rail incident and also the protection of the Choi Yuen Village and suddenly, we were aware that there are many Hong Kong people taking part in agriculture. \r\n\r\nThis picture clearly shows that altogether there are about 110,000 hectares of land in Hong Kong and there are about 4,500 hectares of agricultural land according to the official figures and that accounts for about 4% of the total area of land in Hong Kong. Just now the video has shown that it is about the size of 220 Victoria Park and indeed a huge area. And the dark green portion represents about 700 hectares out of the more than 4,000 hectares, which is less than 5%. The main reason is that according to the news and the government, agriculture is getting unpopular and marginalised by the market. Of course, I’m not going to disagree outright as 95% of vegetables consumed locally every day is from the mainland. But you need to know that at least 1,500 to 2,000 hectares out of the 4,000 hectares of agricultural land are stocked up by property developers. For instance, Ma Shi Po and Kwu Tung, both in the northeast of the New Territories, have a lot of agricultural lands wire-barbed, though surrounding agricultural lands are actually in use. We saw from the news that there are so-called rubble hills in Tin Shui Wai. Those are in fact private lands and are being used for dumping rubble rather than for hiring out for agriculture because, after the agricultural lands are destroyed, their owners may apply for changing their use like for warehouses or residential properties. That is why agriculture is diminishing in Hong Kong. \r\n\r\nNow let’s look at the small red circle at the top. The 70 to 80 hectares are to become the Agricultural Park as suggested by the government in its new agricultural policy consultation about a year ago to support the local agricultural development. You see how big it is in terms of the statutory agricultural land. It’s actually less than 2 percent. My focus is not on the actual effect of the agricultural park but on what will happen to the outer green portion, and why the agricultural park is confined to the red circle only. \r\n\r\n\r\nThis is the total agricultural land as seen before. The self-sufficient ratio of vegetables in Hong Kong in the 60s and 70s when our agriculture peaked was more than 50 percent. In fact, the ratios of many agricultural products are still high today. One of the products fares 60 percent. Can you name it? It’s live chicken. If we work hard on agriculture, we can lift the ratio. Take vegetables again as an example. The ratio has dropped from above 50 percent to 1.9 percent as shown by the dark green portion where vegetables are produced. But if we reuse the 4,000 strong hectares of land, the ratio could be at least 30 percent. Why do we need it? Why grow vegetables by ourselves? Why we not just rely on those from the mainland? I believe more and more people will have a positive view on that and that we need to produce vegetables on our own, whether it’s due to climate change and globing warming, more land turning into desert or dust storm as in Beijing in March. All these speak for the food crisis getting worse. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe benchmark for self-sufficient ratio of vegetables in Singapore is 10 percent and we are in a better position since we have agricultural land and so we can reach up to at least 30 percent. But why our agricultural land is not for agriculture and what the government is up to? In short, our agriculture was very well developed 50 to 60 years ago. In the 50s, the Kadoorie Fund, nowadays the Kadoorie Farm, helped the agricultural development, and the colonial government then had to provide enough food for the immigrants from the mainland or there will be chaos, and it was when China was liberated and the government also feared the infiltration of CCP and so it strived to provide more agricultural land  to new immigrants for them to become self-sufficient. If you can remember, there were a lot of New Territories indigenous inhabitants moving to the UK and Holland running eateries and it was in fact a deliberate policy by the colonial government to release more land for the new immigrants to grow vegetables.\r\n',0,'2021-02-24 18:57:52',NULL,NULL),
(9,9,'演講傳譯	','Chief Justice Roberts, President Carter, President Clinton, President Bush, President Obama, fellow Americans and people of the world, thank you.\r\n\r\nWe, the citizens of America, are now joined in a great national effort to rebuild our country and restore its promise for all of our people.\r\n\r\nTogether, we will determine the course of America and the world for many, many years to come. We will face challenges, we will confront hardships, but we will get the job done.\r\n\r\nEvery four years, we gather on these steps to carry out the orderly and peaceful transfer of power, and we are grateful to President Obama and First Lady Michelle Obama for their gracious aid throughout this transition. They have been magnificent. Thank you.\r\n\r\nToday\'s ceremony, however, has very special meaning because today, we are not merely transferring power from one administration to another or from one party to another, but we are transferring power from Washington, D.C. and giving it back to you, the people.\r\n\r\nFor too long, a small group in our nation\'s capital has reaped the rewards of government while the people have borne the cost. Washington flourished, but the people did not share in its wealth. Politicians prospered, but the jobs left and the factories closed. The establishment protected itself, but not the citizens of our country. Their victories have not been your victories. Their triumphs have not been your triumphs. And while they celebrated in our nation\'s capital, there was little to celebrate for struggling families all across our land.\r\n\r\nThat all changes starting right here and right now because this moment is your moment, it belongs to you.\r\n\r\nIt belongs to everyone gathered here today and everyone watching all across America. This is your day. This is your celebration. And this, the United States of America, is your country.\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat truly matters is not which party controls our government, but whether our government is controlled by the people.\r\n\r\nJanuary 20th, 2017 will be remembered as the day the people became the rulers of this nation again.\r\n\r\nThe forgotten men and women of our country will be forgotten no longer.\r\n\r\nEveryone is listening to you now. You came by the tens of millions to become part of a historic movement, the likes of which the world has never seen before.\r\n\r\nAt the center of this movement is a crucial conviction, that a nation exists to serve its citizens. Americans want great schools for their children, safe neighborhoods for their families, and good jobs for themselves. These are just and reasonable demands of righteous people and a righteous public.\r\n\r\n\r\nBut for too many of our citizens, a different reality exists: mothers and children trapped in poverty in our inner cities; rusted out factories scattered like tombstones across the landscape of our nation; an education system flush with cash, but which leaves our young and beautiful students deprived of all knowledge; and the crime and the gangs and the drugs that have stolen too many lives and robbed our country of so much unrealized potential. This American carnage stops right here and stops right now.\r\n\r\nWe are one nation and their pain is our pain. Their dreams are our dreams. And their success will be our success. We share one heart, one home, and one glorious destiny. The oath of office I take today is an oath of allegiance to all Americans.\r\n\r\nFor many decades, we\'ve enriched foreign industry at the expense of American industry; subsidized the armies of other countries, while allowing for the very sad depletion of our military. We\'ve defended other nations\' borders while refusing to defend our own. And spent trillions and trillions of dollars overseas while America\'s infrastructure has fallen into disrepair and decay. We\'ve made other countries rich, while the wealth, strength and confidence of our country has dissipated over the horizon.\r\n\r\nOne by one, the factories shuttered and left our shores, with not even a thought about the millions and millions of American workers that were left behind. The wealth of our middle class has been ripped from their homes and then redistributed all across the world.\r\n\r\nBut that is the past. And now, we are looking only to the future.\r\n\r\nWe assembled here today are issuing a new decree to be heard in every city, in every foreign capital, and in every hall of power. From this day forward, a new vision will govern our land. From this day forward, it\'s going to be only America first, America first.\r\n\r\nEvery decision on trade, on taxes, on immigration, on foreign affairs will be made to benefit American workers and American families. We must protect our borders from the ravages of other countries making our products, stealing our companies and destroying our jobs.\r\n\r\nProtection will lead to great prosperity and strength. I will fight for you with every breath in my body and I will never ever let you down.\r\n\r\nAmerica will start winning again, winning like never before.\r\n\r\nWe will bring back our jobs. We will bring back our borders. We will bring back our wealth. And we will bring back our dreams.\r\n\r\nWe will build new roads and highways and bridges and airports and tunnels and railways all across our wonderful nation. We will get our people off of welfare and back to work, rebuilding our country with American hands and American labor.\r\n\r\nWe will follow two simple rules; buy American and hire American.\r\n\r\nWe will seek friendship and goodwill with the nations of the world, but we do so with the understanding that it is the right of all nations to put their own interests first. We do not seek to impose our way of life on anyone, but rather to let it shine as an example. We will shine for everyone to follow.\r\n\r\nWe will reinforce old alliances and form new ones and unite the civilized world against radical Islamic terrorism, which we will eradicate from the face of the Earth.\r\n\r\nAt the bedrock of our politics will be a total allegiance to the United States of America, and through our loyalty to our country, we will rediscover our loyalty to each other. When you open your heart to patriotism, there is no room for prejudice.\r\n\r\nThe Bible tells us how good and pleasant it is when God\'s people live together in unity. We must speak our minds openly, debate our disagreements honestly, but always pursue solidarity. When America is united, America is totally unstoppable.\r\n\r\nThere should be no fear. We are protected and we will always be protected. We will be protected by the great men and women of our military and law enforcement. And most importantly, we will be protected by God.\r\n\r\nFinally, we must think big and dream even bigger. In America, we understand that a nation is only living as long as it is striving. We will no longer accept politicians who are all talk and no action, constantly complaining, but never doing anything about it.\r\n\r\nThe time for empty talk is over. Now arrives the hour of action.\r\n\r\nDo not allow anyone to tell you that it cannot be done. No challenge can match the heart and fight and spirit of America. We will not fail. Our country will thrive and prosper again.\r\n\r\nWe stand at the birth of a new millennium, ready to unlock the mysteries of space, to free the earth from the miseries of disease, and to harness the energies, industries and technologies of tomorrow. A new national pride will stir ourselves, lift our sights and heal our divisions.\r\n\r\nIt\'s time to remember that old wisdom our soldiers will never forget, that whether we are black or brown or white, we all bleed the same red blood of patriots.\r\n\r\nWe all enjoy the same glorious freedoms and we all salute the same great American flag.\r\n\r\nAnd whether a child is born in the urban sprawl of Detroit or the wind-swept plains of Nebraska, they look up at the same night sky, they fill their heart with the same dreams, and they are infused with the breath of life by the same almighty creator.\r\n\r\nSo to all Americans in every city near and far, small and large, from mountain to mountain, from ocean to ocean, hear these words: You will never be ignored again.\r\n\r\nYour voice, your hopes, and your dreams will define our American destiny. And your courage and goodness and love will forever guide us along the way.\r\n\r\nTogether, we will make America strong again. We will make America wealthy again. We will make America proud again. We will make America safe again. And yes, together we will make America great again.\r\n\r\nThank you. God bless you. And God bless America.\r\n\r\nThank you.\r\n\r\nGod bless America.\r\n','首席大法官羅伯茨、卡特總統、克林頓總統、布殊總統、奧巴馬總統、美國同胞和全世界人民，謝謝各位。\r\n\r\n\r\n作為美國公民，現在我們全國上下團結一致，為重建我們國家，恢復對我們所有人民的承諾大展宏圖。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們將同心協力決定美國和全世界今後多年的前進方向。我們將面臨各種挑戰；我們將遭遇艱難險阻；但是我們必將完成使命。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們每四年在這個階梯式平台上進行有秩序的權力和平轉移。我們感謝奧巴馬總統和第一夫人米歇爾·奧巴馬恢宏大度，在權力轉移的過程中給予幫助。他們始終高風亮節。謝謝你們。\r\n\r\n\r\n然而，今天的慶典具有極為特殊的意義。因為今天我們不僅僅完成權力從一個政府向另一個政府的轉移，也不僅僅完成權力從一個政黨向另一個政黨的轉移。我們正在將掌握在華盛頓哥倫比亞特區手中的權力交還給你們，廣大的人民。\r\n\r\n長期以來，我國首都有一小部分人獲得政府給予的種種好處，但人民承擔了其中的代價。華盛頓榮華富貴，但人民無法分享其財富。政客獲得功名利祿，但工作機會流失，工廠相繼關閉。現行的制度保護其自身，但不保護我國廣大的公民。他們的勝利從來就不是你們的勝利。他們的偉績從來就不是你們的偉績。他們在我國首都額手相慶的時候，我國各地處境艱難的家家戶戶並沒有什麼值得高興之處。\r\n\r\n這一切都將時移世變，從這裡開始，從現在開始。因為此時此刻屬於你們。完全屬於你們。\r\n\r\n此時此刻屬於今天親臨現場的每一個人，屬於全美各地觀看慶典的每一個人。這個日子是你們的日子。這個慶典是你們的慶典。美利堅合眾國是你們的國家。\r\n\r\n真正重要的問題不是哪一個政黨掌握我們的政府，而是我們的政府是否受人民的控制。\r\n\r\n二零一七年一月二十日將作為人民再次成為這個國家統治者的一天永垂青史。\r\n\r\n\r\n我國被遺忘的男男女女將不再被遺忘。\r\n\r\n\r\n現在每一個人都在傾聽你們的聲音。你們以千萬之眾親臨這個全世界前所未見的歷史性時刻。\r\n\r\n\r\n這個運動的核心是一個重要的信念：一個國家的存在是為了服務於本國公民。美國人民希望自己的子女能夠上優秀的學校，要求家庭居住的社區安全無虞，同時自己能得到良好的工作。這些只不過是堂堂正正的人民和普通大眾的合理需求。\r\n\r\n但是我們眾多的公民則面臨完全不同的現實：在我國各內城區居住的母親和孩子一貧如洗；衰敗荒涼的廠區猶如一座座墓碑散布在我國大地；教育體系耗資巨大，但我們風華正茂的學生被剝奪了學習全部知識的機會。此外，犯罪活動、幫派和毒品奪走了多少人的生命，使我們的國家失去了多少尚未開發的潛力。這種生靈塗炭的現象到此爲止，以現在為終點。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我們是一個國家，他們的痛苦就是我們的痛苦。他們的夢想就是我們的夢想。他們的成功將是我們的成功。我們共有一個心願，一個家園，一個榮耀的命運。我今天的就職宣誓是對全體美國人的效忠宣誓。\r\n\r\n幾十年來，我們繁榮了外國企業但犧牲了美國企業；扶助了其他國家的軍隊，但讓我們的軍隊資源匱乏可悲。我們保護了其他國家的國界但不肯保護我們自己的國界，並且向海外斥資成千上萬億美元，但美國的基礎設施卻變得破舊不堪。我們讓其他國家繁榮起來，但我們國家的財富、實力和信心正在消失天邊。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n一家又一家工廠關閉、離境，絲毫不顧千百萬美國工人被遺棄。我們中產階級家庭的財富被剝奪，被重新分配到世界各地。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n但這一切已經過去，我們現在只需放眼未來。\r\n\r\n我們，今天相聚在此，發出新的指令，它將傳遍每一座城市，每一個外國首都，每一個權力中心。從今天起，我們國家將受一個新願景來指引。從今天起，只有美國第一，美國第一。\r\n\r\n\r\n每一項貿易、稅收、移民、外交決策都將是為了讓美國工人和美國家庭受益。我們必須保護我們的國界，不讓其他國家製造我們的產品，竊取我們的公司，破壞我們的就業。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n實行保護將帶來宏偉的繁榮和實力。我將用我全身的每一分力為你們奮鬥，我將決不會讓你們失望。\r\n\r\n\r\n美國將開始再次贏得勝利，贏得前所未有的勝利。\r\n\r\n我們將恢復我們的就業。我們將恢復我們的邊界。我們將恢復我們的財富。我們將恢復我們的夢想。\r\n\r\n我們將在我們美麗國家的四面八方修築新路，修建高速公路、橋樑、機場、隧道和鐵路。我們將讓人民擺脫救濟，重新就業，用美國人的雙手和美國的勞工重建我們的國家。\r\n\r\n我們將遵循兩條簡單的原則：購買美國貨，僱用美國人。\r\n\r\n我們將謀求與世界各國的友誼和良好關係，但我們是本著這樣的理解去做，即所有國家都有權利將自己的利益放在第一位。我們不謀求把我們的生活方式強加於任何人，而是讓它成為所有人效仿的閃亮發光–我們將閃亮發光–的榜樣。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我們將鞏固原有的聯盟和建立新聯盟，並且團結文明世界對抗極端的伊斯蘭恐怖主義；我們將把它從地球上徹底消滅。\r\n\r\n我們將把政治立基在對美利堅合眾國的絕對效忠，基於對國家的忠誠，我們將重新找到對彼此的忠誠。當你敞開愛國主義的心懷，偏見就沒有存在的餘地。\r\n\r\n\r\n聖經告訴我們，弟兄和睦同居，是何等的善、何等的美。我們必須公開闡明我們的想法，坦誠地辯論我們的不同觀點，但也要始終尋求團結。當美國團結一致時，絕對勢不可擋。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n不應當有恐懼。我們得到保護，而且將一直得到保護。我們將得到我國軍隊和執法機構偉大的男女軍人的保護。而且最重要的是，我們將得到上帝的佑護。\r\n\r\n\r\n最後，我們必須想得更遠並擁有更大的夢想。在美國，我們知道一個國家只有在奮鬥之時才能生存。我們將不再接受只會空談而沒有行動、一味抱怨但從不採取應對措施的政客。\r\n\r\n\r\n空談的時代結束了。行動的時刻已經到來。\r\n\r\n不要讓任何人告訴你這件事辦不到。任何挑戰都無法與美國的心襟、鬥志、和精神相比。我們不會失敗。我們的國家將再度繁榮興盛。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們立足於一個新千年的開端，準備好解開太空之謎，消除地球上的疾病之災，並利用未來的能量、產業和技術。一種新的國家自豪感將令我們振奮，讓我們看得更遠，並彌合我們的分歧。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n現在應當謹記我國軍人永遠都不會忘記的古老道理–不論我們是黑色、棕色還是白色，我們都流淌著同樣鮮紅的愛國者的血。\r\n\r\n我們都享有同樣輝煌的自由，我們都向同一面偉大的美國國旗敬禮。\r\n\r\n\r\n不論一個孩子是出生在底特律不斷延展的城區裡，還是內布拉斯加大風吹過的平原上，他們都抬頭仰望同一片夜空，他們的心中都充滿同樣的夢想，而且他們都被同一個萬能的創世主賦予生命的氣息。\r\n\r\n因此，不論遠近，不論大小，在群山之間、在大海之濱的每個城市中的美國人都請聽這句話：你們不會再被忽視。\r\n\r\n你們的聲音、你們的希望和你們的夢想將決定我們美國的命運。而且你們的勇氣、善良和愛心將永遠為我們指引道路。\r\n\r\n齊心協力，我們將讓美國再度強大。我們將讓美國再度富有。我們將讓美國再度驕傲。我們將讓美國再度安全。而且，是的，齊心協力，我們將使美國再度偉大。\r\n\r\n謝謝你們。上帝保佑你們。上帝保佑美國。\r\n\r\n謝謝你們。\r\n\r\n上帝保佑美國。\r\n','今天我想跟大家分享台灣為什麼需要在宅醫療，以及在宅醫療可以做什麼。這是今年三月份的新聞，聯合報，65歲以上的人口超過345萬，這是台灣。台灣已進入一個高齡的時代。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n世界衛生組織的定義很清楚，高齡人口超過百分之十四，這叫高齡社會。如果說五個人有一個超過65歲，也就是百分之二十，在八年之後我們台灣就要進入超高齡時代。\r\n\r\n講超高齡時代，大家可能覺得很遙遠，可是我們想一想，在我們亞洲，哪一個國家已經是超高齡？我想各位都不陌生，就是日本。其實，今年的台灣只不過是1995年的日本。\r\n\r\n你可以去翻報紙雜誌，1995年的日本是什麼樣子。這個時候的日本面臨的是老人照顧的問題，長照的問題，同時也是在宅醫療的需求開始出現的時候。\r\n\r\n\r\n這是今年二月份朝日新聞的頭版頭條，它寫什麼？他說在宅醫療的需求有一百萬人，一百萬的人口，這個叫作2025年的問題。什麼是2025年的問題？在日本，其實2025年的問題就是日本社會將要進入一個面對所謂多死社會的一個時代。\r\n\r\n多死社會是什麼？我們來看這張圖，綠色的部分就是人在醫院過世，這個就是綠色的部分，然後下面的橘色以及黃色的部份，還有深藍色，是在自己的家裏過世，或者是在長照機構過世。\r\n\r\n但假如說整個環境沒有改變，醫院的數量沒法增加，醫院所能夠承載的死亡就是這麼多，在家裏過世的人又沒有辦法容納更多人的時候，到了2030年的時候，整個日本有47萬的人，他們不曉得在哪裏死亡。\r\n\r\n他們大量的死亡，以至臨終地點，變成是整個社會要面對的一個課題，這個叫做多死社會的問題。這樣的問題，各位覺得台灣會不會發生？覺得會發生的可以舉手嗎？\r\n\r\n因為早上、下午都沒有人叫你們舉手，要叫你們舉一下。我可以跟各位說，台灣一定會發生。紅色這一條線就是日本的死亡人數，其實到了2040年的時候，那個時候日本的死亡人數會到高峰167萬人，然後人口沒有那麼多之後，沒有那麼多人可以死的時候，死亡人數便會下降。\r\n\r\n可是我們政府的推估是下面的綠色的，綠色的那一條一直往上爬升。各位想像一下，如果台灣的人口跟日本人一樣多的規模的話，那就是橘色的那一條線，那我們很厲害，我們到了2045年的時候，我們不但生的比人家少，而且我們比別人還會死，這個時候台灣就超過日本了。\r\n\r\n所以我們未來一樣要面對這樣的問題，那日本現在面對的課題和以至未來日本要面對的問題，解決多死社會就成為在宅，在宅也就成為這個解方。\r\n\r\n我們在宅要做的事情就是支援每個人可以在他熟悉、自在、喜歡的地方，能夠生活到最後這樣子的一個照顧方式，叫做在宅醫療。在宅醫療在日本相對於醫院醫療、門診醫療，被稱為第三種醫療，所以各位以後想到在宅醫療的時候，要用這樣子的角度去看待。\r\n\r\n我想在宅醫療最關鍵的理由是在於有沒有信賴，他們願意這樣子做，讓我們照顧，其實這就是信賴，這個是現代醫療最缺乏的。\r\n\r\n\r\n這樣的信賴必須要基於什麼呢？基於說，在宅醫療的本質就是一種陪伴，不只是醫療，是陪伴，我們要陪伴我們的病人到生命的最後。\r\n','Today I would like to share with you why we need home health care and what it can achieve. This is the United Daily News in March. It says Taiwan’s population over 65 exceeds three million four hundred and fifty thousand. Taiwan has become an aged society.\r\n\r\nAccording to WHO, an aged society has 14 percent of its population above 65. Having 20 percent like what will happen in Taiwan eight years from now will be a super-aged society. \r\n\r\n\r\nThat may sound remote to you, but in Asia we have had one such society. Which one? We know it well, Japan. Today’s Taiwan is Japan in 1995. \r\n\r\n\r\nYou may research if you want to know more about Japan at that time. At that time, Japan faced the problem of health care for the elderly, long-term care, and home health care was in rising demand. \r\n\r\nHere’s the headline of the Asahi Shimbun in February this year. It says one million people need home health care and names this the 2025 Problem. The term means Japan is becoming a high mortality society. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nWhat is it? Look at this chart. The green portion represents the number of people die in hospital. The orange, yellow and dark blue portions are those die at home or long-term care institutions. \r\n\r\nBut if the whole environment doesn’t change and the number of hospitals doesn’t increase, and home health care fails to cater to the needs, four hundred and seventy thousand people will have nowhere to die in Japan by 2030. \r\n\r\nThe number of deaths and the where people die has become a social issue, an issue in a high mortality society. Do you think the like will take place in Taiwan? Raise your hand if you do. \r\n\r\nSince you have not been asked to show your hands, I’d better give it a try. I am sure it will take place in Taiwan. The red line is the number of deaths in Japan. The number will reach one million six hundred and seventy thousand in 2040, to be followed by a downward trend as the population decreases. \r\n\r\n\r\nBut ours as projected by the government is the green line which keeps going up. Imagine if Taiwan is as big as Japan, it will be the orange line. By 2045, we will outdo Japan, with a birth rate lower but a mortality rate higher than Japan.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSo, we are facing the same problem. In Japan, the solution is home health care. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nIn practice, we need to help people get the care they need in places they are familiar with, feel relaxed and like until their final days. This is home health care, which is named the third medical treatment in Japan, after hospitalization and out-patient consultation. This is the right perspective.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe main rationale for home health care lies in trust. People willing to be taken care by us in this way in fact have place their trust on us, and trust is what we need in modern medical treatment. \r\n\r\nBut why they choose to trust? Home health care is in essence not merely medical treatment, but company, one that lasts till the end of our patients’ lives.\r\n',0,'2021-02-24 18:59:58',NULL,NULL),
(10,10,'會議傳譯	','Good morning, good afternoon and good evening.\r\n\r\nWe now have more than six million cases of COVID-19 across the world and have lost more than 370,000 people to the virus. As we work with governments across the world to suppress the virus and accelerate science around diagnostics, therapeutics and vaccines, we also continue to respond to other health emergencies and new disease outbreaks. \r\n\r\nThe Government of the Democratic Republic of the Congo announced today that a new outbreak of Ebola virus disease has been detected near the city of Mbandaka in Équateur province. The announcement follows a complex Ebola outbreak in eastern DRC, which seems to be in its final phase. The new one is on the other side of the DRC in the northwest. WHO will continue supporting DRC in tackling Ebola, as well as responding to COVID-19 and the world’s largest measles outbreak.\r\n\r\nEvery week, WHO continues to provide the world with new and updated technical guidance, based on the best evidence. During this pandemic, we have seen that mass gatherings have the potential to act as super spreading events. To assist groups planning such gatherings, WHO released updated guidance to help organisations determine how and when mass gatherings can safely resume. For example, WHO has worked closely with several sporting organizations including FIFA, UEFA, Formula 1 and religious groups including Organization of Islamic Cooperation, which oversees the Hajj, as they conduct risk assessments around mass gatherings. WHO has updated its risks assessment tool so that organisations can score each risk factor and control measure, which results in an overall risk score. Ultimately WHO advises on the risk assessment and then organizations make the decision on how best to proceed. While we all want sporting events to restart, we want to make sure that it is done as safely as possible.\r\n\r\nWe all know that the impacts of COVID-19 extend well beyond the death and disease caused by the virus itself. The pandemic has forced countries to make difficult choices about suspending some health services. Building on previous guidance on maintaining essential health services through the COVID-19 pandemic, today we are providing operational guidance on how best to put that into practice.\r\n\r\nEnsuring coordination and development of new ways to deliver care while limiting visits to health facilities is key to keeping people safe and ensuring health systems are not overburdened. This means using digital technologies to deliver some routine services remotely, and expanding the amount of medications delivered to the home.\r\n\r\nOne of the areas in which health services have been particularly affected is in care for people with noncommunicable diseases including diabetes, cancer, cardiovascular disease or a chronic respiratory disease.\r\nWe already know that people living with NCDs are more vulnerable to becoming severely ill or dying from COVID-19.\r\n\r\nAt the same time, many people living with noncommunicable diseases are no longer able to access the medicines that they need. WHO conducted a rapid assessment of service delivery for NCDs during the COVID-19 pandemic with 155 countries submitting data. The results released today show that more than half of the countries surveyed have partially or completely disrupted services for treatment of hypertension; half for treatment of diabetes and related complications; and 42% for cancer treatment, and 31% for cardiovascular emergencies. Rehabilitation services have been disrupted in almost two-thirds of countries. The COVID-19 response must therefore be inclusive of the health-care needs of people living with noncommunicable diseases. \r\n\r\nOne of the main causes of NCDs is tobacco. This year’s WHO’s World No Tobacco Day focused on reaching young people to educate them on tobacco industry tactics used to manipulate them into using deadly products that kill 8 million people every year. Even during this global pandemic, where we know tobacco puts users at a higher risk of severe disease and death, the tobacco and nicotine industry persist with their dangerous marketing tactics that aim to attract new users.\r\n\r\nJust as we continue to respond to well-known health threats like tobacco, we’re also responding to one of the most urgent challenges of our time: the threat of antimicrobial resistance. I’m glad to say a record number of countries are now monitoring and reporting on antibiotic resistance - marking a major step forward in the global fight against drug resistance. But the data they provide reveals that a worrying number of bacterial infections are increasingly resistant to the medicines we have traditionally treated them with. As we gather more evidence, it’s clear that the world is losing its ability to use critically important antimicrobial medicines all over the world.\r\n\r\nOn the demand side, in some countries there is an overuse of antibiotics and antimicrobial agents in both humans and animals. However, in many low- and middle-income countries these lifesaving medicines are out of reach for those that need them, leading to needless suffering and death.\r\n\r\nOn the supply side, there is essentially very little market incentive to developing new antibiotics and antimicrobial agents, which has led to multiple market failures of very promising tools in the past few years. As well as finding new models to incentivize sustainable innovation, as seen with the COVID-19 solidarity trial, we must find ways to accelerate viable candidates.\r\n\r\nThe COVID19 pandemic has led to an increased use of antibiotics, which ultimately will lead to higher bacterial resistance rates that will impact the burden of disease and deaths during the pandemic and beyond. In the current Clinical Management of COVID-19, Interim Guidance, WHO has outlined the appropriate use of antibiotic therapy for medical professionals to treat patients. Therefore, both tackling antimicrobial resistance, while also saving lives.\r\n\r\nI will conclude by saying that we have received questions about Friday’s announcement by the President of the United States of America. The world has long benefited from the strong, collaborative engagement with the government and the people of the United States. The US government and people’s contribution and generosity towards global health over many decades has been immense, and it has made a great difference in public health all around the world. It is WHO’s wish for this collaboration to continue.\r\n\r\nI thank you\r\n','大家早上好、下午好、晚上好：\r\n\r\n\r\n現在，全世界已有超過600萬宗新冠肺炎病例，該病毒致使37萬多人失去了生命。我們在與世界各國政府合作阻斷該病毒並加速診斷、治療和疫苗方面的科學發展，與此同時，我們還將繼續應對其他突發衛生事件和新的疾病暴發。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n剛果民主共和國政府今天宣佈，在赤道省姆班達卡市附近發現了新的埃博拉病毒病疫情。在宣佈這一消息之前剛果民主共和國東部地區已經暴發了複雜的埃博拉疫情，當地的疫情似乎進入最後階段。新疫情出現在另一邊，即剛果民主共和國西北地區。世衛組織將繼續支援剛果民主共和國應對埃博拉疫情，同時應對新冠肺炎和世界上最大的麻疹疫情。 \r\n\r\n\r\n世衛組織每周繼續基於最佳證據向世界提供新的和最新的技術指導。在這場大流行期間，我們看到大型集會有可能成為超級傳播事件。為了協助集會等群體規劃，世衛組織發佈了最新指南，以説明各組織確定如何以及何時恢復大型集會才是安全的。例如，世衛組織與包括國際足聯、歐洲足聯、一級方程式在內的若干體育組織以及包括監督朝覲的伊斯蘭合作組織在內的宗教團體密切合作，因為它們對大型集會進行風險評估。世衛組織更新了其風險評估工具，以便各組織可對每項風險因素和每個控制措施打分，最終得出風險總分。最終，世衛組織就風險評估提出建議，隨後各組織就如何最好地進行做出決定。 雖然我們都希望重啟體育賽事，但我們要保證盡可能安全地進行。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n眾所周知，新冠肺炎的影響遠遠超出了病毒本身導致的死亡和疾病。這場大流行迫使各國對於暫停某些衛生服務做出艱難選擇。在先前發佈的在新冠肺炎大流行期間維持基本衛生服務指導檔的基礎上，今天我們就如何將該指導檔最好地付諸實踐提出業務指導。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n確保協調和制定提供護理的新方法，同時限制到衛生設施就診，對於確保人員安全並確保醫療系統不至於不堪重負至關重要。這意味著使用數位技術可以遠端提供一些常規服務，並增加送貨上門的藥物數量。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n衛生服務受到特別影響的領域之一是非傳染性疾病患者就醫，包括糖尿病、癌症、心血管疾病或慢性呼吸道疾病患者。眾所周知，非傳染性疾病患者更容易發展成新冠肺炎重症或死於新冠肺炎。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n與此同時，許多非傳染性疾病患者不再能夠獲得所需藥物。世衛組織在新冠肺炎大流行期間對非傳染性疾病服務提供情況進行了快速評估，有155個國家提交了數據。今天發佈的結果表明，一半以上被調查國家已經部分或完全中斷了高血壓治療服務；一半的糖尿病和相關併發症治療服務；百分之四十二的癌症治療服務和百分之三十一的心血管急症治療服務。在幾乎三分之二的國家中康復服務已經中斷。因此，應對新冠肺炎時必須納入滿足非傳染性疾病患者的衛生保健需求。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n導致非傳染性疾病的主要原因之一是煙草。世衛組織今年的世界無煙日的重點是，讓年輕人瞭解煙草行業採用的策略，這些策略旨在操縱他們使用每年造成800萬人喪生的致命產品。眾所周知，煙草會使煙民面臨更高的重症和死亡風險，即使在這場全球大流行中，煙草和尼古丁行業仍頑固推行其旨在吸引新煙民的危險的行銷策略。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n在我們繼續應對煙草等眾所周知的健康威脅的同時，我們也在應對當代最緊迫的挑戰之一：抗微生物藥物耐藥性的威脅。我高興地告訴大家，現在有數量創紀錄的國家正在監測和報告抗生素耐藥性，這標誌著全球抗藥性鬥爭邁出了重要一步。但是，他們提供的數據表明，細菌感染對傳統上用於治療的藥物越來越具有抗藥性，數量之多令人擔憂。隨著我們收集到更多證據，這些證據表明，世界正在失去使用對全世界而言極其重要的抗微生物藥物的能力。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n從需求側來看，在一些國家，人體和動物都過度使用了抗生素和抗微生物藥物。但是，在許多低收入和中等收入國家，這些救命藥物對於有需求者來說已經是可望不可及，導致不必要的痛苦和死亡。 \r\n\r\n\r\n從供給側來看，開發新的抗生素和抗微生物藥物基本上沒有市場獎勵，在過去幾年導致大有前途的工具在許多市場上失利。正如在新冠肺炎團結試驗中所看到的，除了尋求獎勵可持續創新的新模式外，我們還必須想方設法加速尋求可行的候選藥物。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n新冠肺炎大流行導致抗生素使用增加，最終將導致細菌抗藥性比率提高，這將影響大流行期間及以後的疾病和死亡負擔。在當前的《新冠肺炎臨床管理臨時指南》中，世衛組織概述了衛生專業人員如何適當使用抗生素療法治療患者。 因此，這既解決了抗微生物藥物耐藥性，又挽救了生命。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n最後，我想說的是，我們收到了就美利堅合眾國總統星期五所宣佈事項提出的問題。與美國政府和人民強有力的合作交往使全世界長期受益。幾十年來，美國政府和人民為全球衛生所做貢獻和慷慨捐助舉足輕重，在全世界公共衛生領域發揮了重大作用。世衛組織希望這種合作將繼續下去。 \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n謝謝大家。\r\n','政府發表諮詢文件，建議就美容和健身 服務消費合約設立法定冷靜期，以協助 制訂相關法例，保障消費者權益。諮詢 為期三個月。 \r\n商務及經濟發展局局長邱騰華說，海關 數字顯示，自經修訂的《商品說明條 例》生效至去年年底，共收到 1,124 宗涉 及具威嚇性營業行為的投訴，其中超過 七成投訴關於美容和健身服務業，分別 有 374 和 489 宗。 \r\n我們考慮在這兩個行業引入法定冷靜期 時，我們考慮到不是想將冷靜期作為一 種廣泛適用於每個行業的方式，而是在 一些投訴多、涉及金額大、看到有很多 不良的營商手法，尤其具威嚇性手段普 遍存在的情況，才加入冷靜期的考慮。 \r\n目的正是一方面為消費者提供更大保 障，其實也間接為該行業提供較好的營 商環境，因為商戶不用擔憂在這方面出 現很多爭議。 \r\n諮詢文件建議，冷靜期適用於美容和健 身服務，但不包括只提供美甲、按摩或 改善脫髮服務的商戶，而沒有設置運動 器械的場所以及指定場所的美容或健身 服務，都可獲得豁免。 \r\n此外，冷靜期只適用於預繳 3,000 元或以 上的服務合約。諮詢文件並就冷靜期和 退款期時限，提出兩個選擇方案。 \r\n市民可在商務及經濟發展局工商及旅遊 科網站下載諮詢文件。視乎諮詢結果， 政府的目標是在 2019 至 20 立法年度向立 法會提交相關條例草案。\r\n','The Government has released a  consultation paper with a view to stipulate a  statutory cooling-off period for beauty and  fitness services consumer contracts. Public  views from the three-month public  consultation will help the Government  formulate legislative proposals to protect  consumer rights. \r\nSecretary for Commerce and Economic  Development Edward Yau said that according to the Customs and Excise Department, since the inception of the  Trade Descriptions Ordinance to end of last  year, there were one thousand one hundred  twenty-four complaints involving aggressive  sales tactics, more than 70 percent of which  were connected to beauty and fitness  services, with three hundred seventy-four  and four hundred eighty-nine cases  respectively. \r\nIn proposing a cooling-off period for the two  services, we do not intend to apply the same  to every industry, but only cover situations  involving a considerable amount of money,  unfair trade practices and in particular  aggressive sales tactics. \r\nThe aim is to better protect consumers as  well as to provide a better business  environment for the named services as  shops will be able to stay away from  troubles after the policy comes into effect. \r\nThe proposed cooling-off period applies to  beauty and fitness services consumer  contracts with exemptions for places that  only provide nail treatment, massage or hair  loss improvement services. Places not  equipped with exercise machines or other designated places that provide beauty and  fitness services are also exempted. \r\nThe cooling-off period is only applicable to  contracts that involve a pre-payment of  $3,000 or more. And there are two proposed  options for the cooling-off length and refund  periods. \r\nThe public consultation paper can be  downloaded from the website of the  Commerce, Industry and Tourism Branch of  the Commerce and Economic Development  Bureau. Subject to the outcome of the  consultation, the Government aims to  introduce the bill into the Legislative Council  in the 2019-20 legislative session. \r\n',0,'2021-02-24 19:02:38',NULL,NULL),
(11,11,'議會傳譯	','我們繼續2019年強制性公積金計劃（修訂）條例草案的三讀。鄺俊宇議員。\r\n\r\n\r\n主席，今天是這一期的會期的最後一次大會，有幸在這次最後一次會議發言，真是與有榮焉，亦是正在說我們這個強積金計劃的條例草案的三讀。我在對上一次已經說過，開宗明義很簡單告訴局長，你問我，我是全盤否定強制性退休金計劃，做便做全民退休保障， OK ？但是今天必須在三讀一個討論非常之窄的範圍下，盡我能力發揮啦，OK？必須要說一說，因為這個積金易的平台公司，即是說將28個積金計劃和12個計劃的行政平台統一到同一個中央電子平台簡化程序和降低成本，我不信的。你無非是搵香港人老襯，強積金是給退休生活保障，大家也知，政府時常說的，退休生活三大支柱：私人儲蓄、強積金和綜援，說了也不知說了什麼，拿綜援就是退休的保障，私人儲蓄是我自己的，關你鬼事，到強積金，就是他們最榮幸的，就是這一樣東西是我們做的，但可憐至連通脹也追不上的強積金，在過去的時間近乎被批評一事無成，到今天做這些小修小補，也是於事無補，就是說，我現在做過中央電子平台，給你簡化程序，你可以loop你的資料看看有哪一個戶口，結合起來了，以往是分散的， 是不是？20年了，實行了20年了，今天和我們說做個中央電子平台，便覺得是個位大的向前跨一步，我只是針對中央電子平台的話，我可以講，講不完，今天只得4小時，是不是？但在這個三讀階段，我要清楚告訴你，這個強積金是不能保障打工仔的退休生活的，OK？有多少老人家執紙皮執鋁罐，他們的生活的晚年落得這麼淒涼……\r\n\r\n鄺俊宇議員，請你返回這個辯論好嗎？（主席，我差不多每句都返回題目，不是嗎？）我也有責任提醒你我們不是在辯論強積金的優劣，而是2019年強制性公積金計劃（修訂）條例草案，請你返回這個辯論好嗎？\r\n\r\n彥哥，已經是最後一晚，為什麼這樣？我很簡單，我必定緊貼題目來說，昨天給你四度打斷了，我也能發言15分鐘，今晚我必定盡說，OK？假如我真的非常離題，主席，你提一提我好嗎？很簡單，我是全盤否定強積金，但我現在不是跟你討論強積金的利弊，而是你這個修訂，說降低行政成本，令行政費有望減低，你也知道行政費貴嗎？你也知道強積金的行政費貴嗎？基金公司是在強積金計劃中永恆的贏家，輸家就是我們每位打工仔，就是這麼簡單。你現在跟我們說即將註冊計劃那些費用不會轉嫁到計劃成員上，信我，做這個電子平台方便開始做這個對沖，取消對沖。對沖真的很離譜，對沖的錢是我們儲起的，老闆要的時間要炒我，那些長期服務金便在那裏扣，你便說現在這個電子平台可以做到這件事，邁向這個方向，二十年了，現在才邁向這個方向？給二十年你弄強積金也弄不成，應該要立即做這個全民退休保障，不是嗎？真的很可憐，強積金，顧名思義是強制性公積金，大家也知，總之就是到65歲，你有得搣的，好了，但是我們每日便望着那個款項，你現在弄個中央電子平台給我望着，望着自己每日虧損多少，更慘，你會向我說，強積金，議員，不要緊的，看長線，幾十年的，現在不是幾十年了？幾十年後才問你取回金錢，在其間，我其實我有什麼大病，病也不可以取回金錢，在座有很多議員同事也知道，曾經幫助很多基層市民，你真的病至入骨也不能取回強積金，你只有幾個情況才可以取回。現在這個中央電子平台，今天的金科玉律啊大佬，要為了自己不離題，隔幾句便要說中央電子平台，你才能夠緊扣議題，你弄個中央電子平台給我看是沒用的，我看自己虧蝕了多少錢，今天又虧蝕了，首三個月，每個打工仔虧蝕37,000元，今年啊，知不知道？即是你什麼也不用做，你便虧蝕了37,000 元，你說，基金公司真的是賺大錢的，整個強積金總資產是9,690億，去年業界，說的是整個業界的收入是141億，已經創新高，一再創新高，我相信局長都有同感，局長是新來的，很痛苦啊，弄這個東西給我，我不知怎樣做。百病叢生，怎樣醫也有問題，怎樣醫也是百花藥費，但是今天在三讀這個階段，你問我，我會跟你說，強積金一定要過渡到全民退休保障，你不要給我整色整水，二十年三十年，仍是給我弄個電子平台，減低行政費，減低成本，這樣便對打工仔有利，是有利的，但這些有利也有相對有利，還是絕對有利，相對有利就是我少收你一點，絕對有利就是計劃本身有問題，行錯方向，搵老襯，就是這麼簡單。\r\n','We resume Mandatory Provident Fund Schemes (Amendment) Bill 2019 third reading. Kwong Chun Yu.\r\n\r\nPresident, today is the last council meeting of this term. So I am honoured to be speaking here. And we are now discussing the Mandatory Provident Fund Schemes (Amendment) Bill 2019. As I said last time, I am totally against the scheme. I am for universal retirement protection. And now I have to speak within a narrow scope. Now the eMPF platform company, the 12 schemes will be unified under the electronic platform. I don’t have faith in it. Hong Kong people will be taken for a ride. Now the MPF is for a safeguard during retirement and it said the government said that this is one of the three pillars, the MPF, private savings and the so ah this is a claim as an achievement, but, however, the MPF doesn’t even catch up with inflation. It has been fruitless. This is a small step and now you say you have a centralised electronic platform. The streamlining of the procedures would enable you to look at your performance. It’s been 20 years and this is supposed to be a great step forward. The centralised electronic platform, well, we have only four hours, we can’t say that much, but at the third reading stage, I can tell you that this MPF scheme is no safeguard for retirement protection. Many elderly, they scavenge for cardboard and cans…\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nMr Kwong, please come back to this topic. I have the duty to remind you that we are not debating the pros and cons of the MPF schemes but the amendment bill itself. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThis is the last evening so I will stick to this topic. Now I was interrupted by you four times yesterday. I only spoke fifteen minutes. President, now I am wholly against the MPF schemes. I am talking about the amendment. It’s supposed to reduce administration fee. You know the administration fee is expensive. The fund companies are always the winners under the scheme. The losers are the employees. You tell us that the annual registration fees will not be shouldered by the scheme members. Now this will be a step for cancelling the offset of the MPF benefits. Now the employers fire their employees and they can offset against the MPF benefits. Now you have done that for 20 years. It’s a failure. You should immediately embark upon universal retirement protection. Now you are supposed to have the benefits by age 65. Now you let me look at the poor performance on the electronic platform to see how much money I have lost. You say that doesn’t matter. You have to take the long-term perspective. That’s what you say. And even when I’m suffering a major illness, I cannot withdraw the benefits. Only under several conditions and you have the centralised platform. So I have to mention the platform every now and then. It’s useless. I just see how much money I have lost. For the first three months this year, each employee loses 37,000 dollars. The fund companies make big money. The total assets of the fund industry 967 billion dollars. Now the secretary is new in his job. Now this is a tough job for him. It has all sorts of problems. Now we are at third reading stage. I tell you that the MPF schemes must progress towards universal retirement protection. You tell us that the platform will reduce the administration fees is beneficial but it’s only relative. The scheme in fact is all wrong. It’s in the wrong direction.\r\n','Well, I thank you, Mr. Moy. I have to tell you, there is one really disappointing thing to me, and that is I frequently speak to Assistant Secretary Danny Russel on the phone about different issues, and I believe he intended to be here to testify. I believe I talked to him twice about it. But time after time, and this is something that the Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific has talked to me about, for whatever reason, the administration pulls the witnesses. And I know it isn\'t a lack of engagement on the part of Danny Russel’s part because we have talked to him repeatedly about issues. But there is something about the relationship here with \r\nthe State Department, when Eliot Engel and I make these requests, or Subcommittee Chairman Chabot on the Asia and the Pacific Subcommittee with Mr. Faleomavaega, for some reason the witnesses are always cancelled. And what we want to talk about is Asia policy. And, as far as I know, Danny Russel and I are in concurrence on a lot of these issues, but I don\'t know about further up in the administration. So when I asked questions, for some reason, the State Department… I am going to ask you a question now, for example. As I mentioned in my opening statement, I strongly believe that Taiwan should be included in the Trans-Pacific Partnership. Does the U.S. Government support Taiwan\'s inclusion in the TPP? That is my question to you. Can you \r\nspeak, you know, on behalf of the administration here?\r\n\r\nThank you very much. I do appreciate your comments. And I did have a chance to speak to Danny Russel before coming up, and he wanted me to pass on his regrets and also his appreciation for your setting up this meeting. I can say that, from our part, I don\'t think that there is anything preventing us from talking about Taiwan issues here…   \r\n\r\nWell, it is not just Taiwan. If Subcommittee Chairman Chabot wasn\'t equally concerned about this, equally disappointed, as he brought up with the Secretary of State here yesterday, I probably wouldn\'t bring it up. But it is just a pattern that, at this point. To us, the Asia-Pacific region is vitally important. We spend a lot of time on it, on this issue, and we want the administration to be equally engaged on this. And so, if you will carry that information back…\r\n\r\nI will.\r\n\r\nBut, again, particularly given Taiwan\'s almost singular reliance on cross-Strait trade, does the U.S. Government support Taiwan\'s inclusion in the TPP?\r\n\r\nWell, thank you. And I will relay those comments to my colleagues. It certainly isn\'t a statement about our commitment to very strong U.S.-Taiwan unofficial relations. In fact, I think that we have a very strong record, and I think we have a very good story to tell about that. With regard to your question about TPP, we welcome Taiwan\'s interest in it. And we have heard from them very recently about their interest. We also welcome…and I think that you met with President Ma Ying-jeou on your recent congressional delegation. But we welcome his steps to liberalize Taiwan\'s economy. I think that as you know, we are in ongoing negotiations on TPP, and I think what I can say about this is that, you know, perhaps it is best if we move toward conclusion on those negotiations before we discuss additional membership. But I think that, you know, we are taking a step-by-step approach here. We have heard from Taiwan, as well as others, about interest in TPP, and we certainly, again, welcome that interest. And we are willing to definitely consider, along with some countries that have approached us most recently. We are willing to discuss TPP in the future.\r\n\r\nWell, one of the most important aspects of TPP beyond the important trade-related benefits is that the grouping will help shape East Asia\'s multilateral political architecture by firmly anchoring nation-states in a binding legal agreement. I want to make certain that Taiwan is part of that agreement.\r\n','嗯，多謝你，莫先生。我想告訴你，有一件事情令我很失望，就是我時常跟助理國務卿丹尼爾·羅素通電話，討論不同的問題，我相信他有意出席這個會議作證。我應該跟他說過兩次。但每一次都是這樣，這是亞太小組跟我說過的，不管是什麼原因，當局總是不讓證人出席。我知道這不是丹尼爾·羅素不想，因為我已經跟他討論過很多次。但是這個會議跟國務院的關係出了問題，不論艾略特·恩格爾與我要求，或是亞太小組主席夏伯特跟法里歐馬維加先生提出，因為某些原因，作證都被取消。我們想談的是亞洲政策，而就我所知，丹尼爾·羅素與我在很多問題上立場一致，但我不知道政府高層的意向。所以每次我提出問題，因為某些原因，國務院⋯⋯我現在想向你提出問題。剛才致開幕詞時我提到，我極之相信台灣應該加入跨太平洋夥伴關係協定。美國政府是否支持台灣加入協定？這就是我向你提出的問題。你可不可以代表政府在這裏回應？\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n十分感謝你的問題。我衷心欣賞你的評語。事實上我出席這個會議之前，有機會跟丹尼爾·羅素交談，他希望我在這個會議上轉達他的遺憾，同時感謝你安排這個會議。我可以按國務院的立場說，我們沒有理由不可以在這會議上談台灣問題⋯⋯\r\n\r\n不單是台灣。如果小組主席夏伯特沒有同樣感到憂慮，同樣失望，正如他昨天在這裏向國務卿表示他的看法，我也不會今天提出這個問題。但是在這問題上，已經成了一種慣性。亞太地區對我們非常重要，我們花了很多時間討論亞太地區問題，我們希望政府同樣關心，所以希望你可以將這個訊息轉達⋯⋯\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我會。\r\n\r\n\r\n不過我得再說，尤其台灣差不多一面倒倚賴中台海峽貿易，美國政府會否支持台灣加入協定？\r\n\r\n多謝。我會將你的評語轉達給同事。當然，這並非我們對美台非官方關係的承諾宣言，事實上我認為我們雙方有非常良好的紀錄，我們有非常出色的歷史。至於協定，我們歡迎台灣表示有意加入。而我們才剛剛知道他們有興趣，我們亦歡迎⋯⋯我知道你最近率領國會代表團與馬英九總統會面，我們歡迎他採取措施開放台灣經濟。我相信你也知道，我們正在進行協定的談判，我能夠說的是，最理想是我們先完成這些談判，才討論加入新成員。你也明白，我們正在逐步工作。我們知道台灣與其他地方有興趣加入這個協定，我們當然十分歡迎。我們必定會一併考慮最近與我們接觸的國家。我們會再討論這個協定。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n這個協定非常重要，不單是因為關乎貿易的利益，而是這協定有助塑造東亞多邊政治架構，藉具約束力的法律協議把各國牢固地組織起來。我要確保台灣加入這個協定。\r\n',0,'2021-02-24 19:03:39',NULL,NULL),
(12,12,'法庭傳譯	','','','','',0,'2021-02-24 19:03:56',NULL,NULL),
(13,13,'實例分析與總結	','The average student takes notes at a rate of one-third of a word per second. The average teacher speaks about two to three words per second. Bottom line, if you\'re trying to copy down everything your teacher is saying while he drones on about Shakespeare, you\'re going to fall seriously behind.\r\n\r\nNote-taking is an important skill in and out of school. You can make the difference between passing and failing a test, excelling at a job or even enjoying a complicated movie. And most of us don\'t do it well.\r\n\r\n\r\nWe\'re going to give you a three-step method for taking notes that will actually help you learn. Numerous studies over the years have proven what\'s already pretty obvious. People who take notes remember the material better than those who don\'t.\r\n\r\nBut how much better? A 1970s\' study by developmental psychologist Michael Howe found the students were seven times more likely to remember facts one week after hearing them if they took notes. But here\'s the thing, most people don\'t know how to take notes.\r\n\r\nWe\'re taught from a very young age that when a teacher starts delivering a load of information. For example: \"Shakespeare described Romeo and Juliet\'s love as star-crossed.\" That we should start writing down as much what they\'re saying as possible. Well, this is an incredibly inefficient way to take notes.\r\n\r\nWhy? You\'re not actually learning anything.\r\nYou\'re simply acting as a human audio recorder. A recorder by the way that only picks up one out of every ten words. And you\'re saving the learning for later when you\'ll have an even less complete lesson plan to look over.\r\n\r\nNote-taking should actually act as a form of learning. Something that helps you work your way through the lesson as the teacher is giving it. So that when you leave the classroom (you) already understand the concepts. So how do you do that?\r\n\r\nWe have a three-step method for taking the kind of notes that force you to learn the material inside the classroom and not out. Pause and print the sheet and put it in your binder. Ready for your next class. Finished? Okay let\'s go!\r\n\r\nStep one: don\'t write down facts. Write down conclusions. Don\'t worry about capturing every single thing your teacher is saying. Spend more time listening, trying to understand the lecture. When you do start writing, format your notes as a series of questions posed by the teacher\'s lecture, (and then) fill in your own answers.\r\n\r\nFor example, question: What is the central theme in Romeo and Juliet? Conclusion: More than being a tragic love story, Romeo and Juliet is about the consequences of deeply held grudges.\r\n\r\nThis way, you\'re recording the importance of what the teacher is saying and not just raw facts. When you do need to include data, add only the most important points under each question. This is the evidence for each question\'s answer.\r\n\r\nStep two: use colored pens. Yap that\'s right! This will help you remember your notes visually. Also, if you establish a set template for your notes, you\'ll be able to take them more efficiently. Write questions in red, definitions in blue, conclusions in green.\r\n\r\nStep three: review your notes, don\'t relearn them. Spend at least ten minutes organizing your notes after class. Wanna test your comprehension? Try teaching the material to a classmate. This will be a great marker to see if you\'ve actually learned anything.\r\n\r\nNote-taking is a valuable life skill that doesn\'t lose its utility when you graduate. Find ways to integrate note-taking in your daily life. You\'ll soon find yourself in the exclusive and creative group of people. Bring out their Moleskines at lectures, movies, and TED (Talks).\r\n\r\nAlright Wellcasters, let\'s recap. Today we learned how to take notes in a way that ensures you learn the material during class time and not after. First, write down your conclusions instead of a barrage of facts. Second, use your questions to make connections. And third, spend 10 minutes going over these notes at the end of class. And if you should choose, try going over these notes by teaching them to a classmate or friend.\r\n\r\nOkay, did these tips help? Let us know!\r\nOr if (you) have a wellness topic that you\'d like it to see covered, shoot us an email. We\'d love to see your notes! \r\n','一般學生記筆記的速度是一秒記下三分之一個字。一般老師的授課速度大概是一秒講兩到三個字。重點是，如果你嘗試把老師所說關於莎士比亞的內容全記下來，你遠遠趕不上。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n不論你是否學生，做筆記都是很重要的技巧，决定你能否通過考試、工作表現好壞、甚至能否享受一部劇情複雜的電影。但大部分的人都不懂如何做好筆記。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們要教你做筆記的三步驟，可以真正幫助你學習。過去，很多研究證明了一個顯而易見的事實。做筆記比沒做筆記的記得牢固。\r\n\r\n\r\n但是差多少呢？在 1970 年代的研究中，發展心理學家 Michael Howe 的研究顯示，有抄筆記的學生在一星期後，會比沒有抄筆記的人更容易記住事實，差別是七倍。問題是，很多人都不知道該怎麼做筆記。\r\n\r\n\r\n我們從很小的時候就被老師灌輸一大堆資訊。舉例說：「莎士比亞形容羅密歐與茱麗葉是一對命運多舛的戀人。」於是我們應該開始盡可能寫下老師所說的話。其實，這是一個非常沒效率的做筆記方法。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n為什麼？因為你其實沒有在學任何東西。你只不過是一個人聲錄音機，而且只能每10 個字裡面記錄下 1 個字。之後你拿着不完整的課堂筆記，才開始學習。\r\n\r\n\r\n做筆記應該是一種學習模式，幫助你在老師講課時順利學習。這樣，當你上完課時，你也已經了解基本概念了。那麼如何做得到？\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n我們有三個步驟的方法來記筆記，迫使你在上課時就學得到，而不是下課後才吸收。先暫停，把學習單印下來，放在你的資料夾內，準備下一個課程。好了嗎？那麼開始囉！\r\n\r\n\r\n步驟一：不要寫下事實。要寫下結論。不要急著抄下老師說的每一個字。花時間聆聽，嘗試了解內容。到開始記筆記，把筆記寫成一系列老師提出的問題，加上你自己的答案。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n比方來說，問題：羅密歐與朱麗葉這部劇作的中心思想是什麼？結論：不單是一個愛情悲劇，還是深仇大恨所造成的結果。\r\n\r\n\r\n這樣下來，你記錄了老師說的重點而不只是單純的事實。如果真的需要寫下一些參考資料，只把重點記在每個問題底下，幫助證明你寫的答案正確。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n步驟二：使用顏色筆。沒錯！這在視覺上幫你記住內容。如果有一套筆記規公式，可以更有效率地抄筆記。用紅色寫問題，用藍色寫定義，用綠色寫結論。\r\n\r\n\r\n步驟三：筆記是用來複習，而不是用來學習。下課後至少花十分鐘整理筆記。想知道自己吸收了多少嗎？嘗試講述筆記內容給同學聽。這能測驗你是否真正學到。\r\n\r\n\r\n做筆記是個很有價值的生活技能，就算你不再是學生仍然受用。找機會將做筆記融合於日常生活中吧！你很快會發現自己成為獨具一格又有創意的人，帶著 Moleskines 筆記本去上課、看電影、聽 TED 演講那種。\r\n\r\n\r\n好的 Wellcasters，咱們來複習一遍吧！今天我們學習了如何做筆記，確保你可以在課堂中學習，而不是課後。第一，寫下你的結論而不是只是一大堆事實。第二，以問題為線索。第三，下課後花十分鐘重看筆記。可以將筆記內容講述給同學或朋友聽，當作複習。\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n好的，這些技巧有幫助嗎？讓我們知道！如果你有關於健康的主題，想要我們製作成影片，請電郵給我們。我們期待你的訊息！\r\n','','',0,'2021-02-24 19:05:15',NULL,NULL);

/*Table structure for table `tbl_unit` */

DROP TABLE IF EXISTS `tbl_unit`;

CREATE TABLE `tbl_unit` (
  `id` int(11) unsigned NOT NULL AUTO_INCREMENT COMMENT 'Unit ID',
  `name` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL COMMENT 'Unit Name',
  `number` int(11) unsigned NOT NULL COMMENT 'Unit Number',
  `title` varchar(255) COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL COMMENT 'Unit Title',
  `description` text COLLATE utf8mb4_unicode_ci NOT NULL COMMENT 'Unit Description',
  `is_deleted` tinyint(1) unsigned NOT NULL DEFAULT 0,
  `created_at` datetime NOT NULL,
  `updated_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  `deleted_at` datetime DEFAULT NULL,
  PRIMARY KEY (`id`)
) ENGINE=InnoDB AUTO_INCREMENT=14 DEFAULT CHARSET=utf8mb4 COLLATE=utf8mb4_unicode_ci;

